<1ST_LINE>d a BC-Dance     06-18 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danes Dance Exotic `Abdallah' in NY</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The yearning for the Eastern and exotic which
made ``Scheherazade'' popular is seen in August Bournonville's 1855
ballet ``Abdallah.''
   The Royal Danish Ballet danced it with grace and beauty Friday
night, as part of its week-long Metropolitan Opera season.
   Bournonville created exciting dancing for men and these tall
Danish dancers looked splendid. The women are precise but in a
small-scaled way; their dancing is delicate and graceful. Heidi
Ryom as Irina was the most sweetly feminine of them all.
   Linda Hindberg had a small part but a good one, as the leader of
a harem, a part which allowed the ballerina to show strength in her
presentation. Alexander Kolpin was striking, in appearance and
dancing, in the title role.
   Bournonville told stories with charming simplicity and no
subplots. He wove in subtle mime gestures which explained
conversations, carrying the plot forward.
   ``Abdallah'' was out of the Royal Danish Ballet's repertory from
1858 to 1985, when the late dancer Toni Lander and dancer Flemming
Ryberg reconstructed it from Bournonville's notations on the Holger
Simon Paulli music score.
   It isn't as fast moving as ``Napoli,'' with which the Danes
opened the Met season, but it is equally as delightful.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
