<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ExtraditionDenied     06-18 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Extradition Denied,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magistrate Refuses Extradition of Suspected Terrorist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal magistrate has rejected a government
request to extradite a man to Israel to face charges in a 1986
terrorist bombing in Jerusalem, saying he was likely acting to
achieve a political aim.
   U.S. Magistrate John Caden ruled Friday there was ``probable
cause to believe'' that the defendant, Mahmoud Abed Atta, 34,
committed the bombing ``in furtherance of the political objective''
of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Therefore, Caden said Atta, who also uses the name Mahmoud
El-Abed Ahmad, was protected under the ``political offense
exception'' of U.S. law and placed him outside the jurisdiction of
the extradition treaty between the United States and Israel.
   Caden also said he had no governance over the case because Atta
had been brought to the United States ``in a constitutionally
impermissible manner.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Gleeson said the government would
seek an immediate stay of the order pending a possible appeal or
other recourse.
   ``While this court does not approve the actions taken by Ahmad,
nor does it desire to express support for either side in this
conflict, the fact remains that the conflict exists and that the
political offense exception was formulated to protect the rights of
those, whose philosophy may differ from ours, to fight for a way of
life they believe in,'' Caden said in a 72-page written decision.
   His order ``expresses no opinion as to the legitimacy of the
Palestine objectives, the Israeli treatment of the Arabs or the
legitimacy of the occupancy of the West Bank,'' he said.
   Atta, who has been described by the FBI as a member of the PLO,
has been charged with hurling a firebomb into a bus on April 12,
1986 in the Israeli-occupied West Bank. The bus driver was killed
and eight passengers were injured. Two other people have been
convicted in Israel of participating in the attack.
   Atta has been held without bail at the federal Metropolitan
Correctional Center in Manhattan since his arrest in May 1987
during a flight from Venezuela to Kennedy Airport.
   Atta, who was born in Ramala on the West Bank and became an
American citizen in 1982, was held on an extradition warrant from
Israel, which does not have a treaty with Venezuela.
   A call to Atta's lawyer, Ramsey Clark, for comment was not
returned.
</TEXT>
