<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Economy     06-18 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Economy,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unions Demand Pay Hikes As Prices Rise After Government Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has rejected as unreal
the demands of two opposition unions for a 600 percent wage
increase as prices soared in the wake of free-market economic
reforms.
   The leftist Sandinista government said the demands of the
Workers' Federation of Nicaragua and General Federation of
Independent Workers were inflationary. Both federations are
controlled by the opposition Socialist Party.
   Authorities on Wednesday announced a huge devaluation of the
cordoba, Nicaragua's currency, a near-doubling of gasoline prices
and a general pay increase of 30 percent.
   A dollar was worth 80 cordobas at the official rate but fetched
250 cordobas on the black market Friday. Before the devaluation it
was worth 13 cordobas at the official rate.
   While the government retained subsidies for some basic foods,
prices in markets outside the rationing system soared. The cost of
a liter of milk, just over a quart, jumped from 6.6 to 21 cordobas;
a pound of meat from 50 to 100 cordobas; and a dozen eggs from 50
to 80 cordobas.
   Cab drivers ignored the official tariff of 5 cordobas for a
short trip and demanded 20. Many who own their taxis simply stayed
home on Friday.
   The primary school teachers guild announced their pay of 2,500
cordobas a month was not enough to live on. President Daniel Ortega
said he would meet with the teachers Sunday.
   While no public protests of the economic measures were held,
Ortega warned domestic critics Thursday they were ``playing with
fire'' by opposing the program.
</TEXT>
