<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe 1stAdd   06-18 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe, 1st Add,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHN: active investigation.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The 2-year-old investigation centers on allegations that defense
contractors received secret information from former government
officials whom they hired as consultants. Public officials were
bribed as part of the scheme, according to a search warrant.
   CBS News, citing an unidentified administration official,
reported Friday that seven Defense Department employees are
suspected of accepting bribes or gifts in return for inside
information on Pentagon contracts.
   And ABC News reported that unidentified officials said the
payoffs run into millions of dollars in cash in addition to gifts
and cars.
   Sen. John Warner of Virginia, ranking Republican on the Armed
Services Committee, said Friday the investigation is producing
``the most widespread case I or anyone else has ever seen.''
   Sen. Charles Grassley, an Iowa Republican who sits on the
committee, said in a Senate speech that the matter is ``widespread,
beyond the wildest imagination of what's going on.''
   Chappell, D-Fla., chairman of the House appropriations
subcommittee on defense, characterized as a ``bunch of bunk'' a
report Friday in The Los Angeles Times that he is under scrutiny in
the case. Chappell's panel oversees defense spending.
   A company in Chappell's congressional district, Armtec Inc. of
Palatka, Fla., is one of 15 defense contractors whose offices were
searched by FBI agents Tuesday.
   Armtec's president, William W. Roberts, is a personal friend of
the Chappell's. He said his company ``is not aware of any
wrongdoing'' and will cooperate with investigators.
   Chappell's financial disclosure form for 1987 shows that he
accepted $3,000 in speaking fees from defense firms searched by the
FBI.
   At the center of the investigation is former Pentagon official
Melvyn Paisley, whose office was bugged and telephone tapped for
two years.
   Paisley, assistant secretary of the Navy for research,
engineering and systems from 1981 to April 1987, is now a
Washington consultant to numerous defense contractors, including
McDonnell Douglas Corp. and United Technologies Corp. Both
companies had offices that were searched Tuesday.
   Also being looked at is retired four-star Adm. James A. ``Ace''
Lyons, who sources say was a colleague of Paisley's. Lyons is not
accused of any wrongdoing, but a warrant authorizing a search of
McDonnell Douglas offices in St. Louis sought, among other things,
documents ``relating to the work of Ace Lyons for McDonnell Douglas
from December 1987 through 1988.''
   Both Paisley and Lyons were close associates of former Navy
Secretary John F. Lehman Jr.
   The Washington Post reported today that former Defense Secretary
Caspar Weinberger was told when he held that office that Lehman's
office was a ``principal point of origin'' for leaks of classified
budgetary documents relating to contracts and that at least five
people had ``continuously disclosed classified documents.''
   The undated, unsigned ``talking paper'' filed in federal court
in Alexandria, Va., in early 1986, was prepared in connection with
a pending criminal case against a former defense consultant. The
Post said law enforcement officials that it did not identify said
the document is unrelated to the defense fraud probe.
   A government source told The Associated Press on Friday night
that during a meeting between Henry Hudson, the U.S. attorney
conducting the investigation, and Grassley, the senator asked
Hudson whether Lehman was a target of the investigation and Hudson
replied, ``No comment.''
   The New York Times reported today that two major military
contractors, the Martin Marietta Corp. and the LTV Corp., disclosed
Friday that they were under scrutiny as part of the investigation.
   The companies also acknowledged, the Times reported, that at one
time both had retained the services of Paisley and a colleague of
his, William Galvin.
</TEXT>
