<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Haiti 1stLd-Writethru a0405 06-18 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0405,0690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civilian President Ousts Army Commander for Insubordination</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The communique ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with Namphy having no immediate response to his firing. PICKS up
5th graf, `At the ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ President Leslie Manigat has fired
his armed forces commander and two other generals to cap the first
major confrontation between the new civilian government and the
powerful military.
   A presidential communique read on national television late
Friday said Manigat had retired Commander in Chief Lt. Gen. Henri
Namphy and two other members of the general staff, brigadier
generals Carl Michel Nicholas and Wilton Cherisson.
   Namphy led a three-man junta that governed Haiti for two years
until Manigat won a popular election in January. At the time,
critics lambasted Manigat as the military's puppet.
   Namphy had no immediate public response to the move.
   The communique said Namphy and other army officers had defied
Manigat's decision Wednesday to rescind an order tranfering and
retiring several high-ranking officers.
   At the center of the struggle is Col. Jean-Claude Paul, indicted
on drug-trafficking charges earlier this year by a grand jury in
Miami. Namphy wanted to demote him to an administrative post while
Manigat opposed the move.
   Manigat said Namphy's order was unconstitutional because it was
made without consulting him. The constitution names the president
as ``nominal'' chief of the armed forces and the head of the army
as the ``effective'' commander.
   ``A struggle has begun between Manigat, Namphy and Jean-Claude
Paul. Someone will have to come out on top. The personal security
of each man is at stake,'' said Hubert de Ronceray, runner-up to
Manigat in the junta-run Jan. 17 elections.
   ``Manigat was named president. He wants to prove he is not a
puppet. He will go all the way to the end,'' de Ronceray said in a
telephone interview after Namphy was fired.
   ``Perhaps he is acting by stages, to get one military man after
another under control, finally to win the good graces of the
Americans,'' he said.
   U.S. officials have backed popular elections and civilian
control in Haiti, one of the poorest countries in the Western
Hemisphere.
   Another major presidential candidate in the elections, Gregoire
Eugene, said, ``As soon as the first presidential communique was
issued on Wednesday, we should have expected a followup. We will
have to wait and see what happens.''
   Manigat appeared to have aligned himself with Paul when he
rescinded Namphy's order transferring Paul as commander of the
700-man Dessalines Barracks to assistant chief of staff. The
Dessalines Barracks is one of the nation's most feared army units,
and Paul reportedly refused to accept the transfer.
   Soldiers under Paul's command were blamed for widespread
violence against voters that forced cancellation of November's
independently administered general elections and left more than 30
people dead.
   It was not clear why Namphy ordered the transfer. His order
could represent a power struggle within the army, or the transfer
may involve the drug-running charges against Paul, who has denied
the accusations.
   Nicolas, one of the fired generals, denied earlier this year
that Paul was involved in drug trafficking and accused the foreign
press of singling him out for attack.
   Manigat took over on Feb. 7 from Namphy as Haiti's chief
executive. Namphy had been president of the three-man junta since
then President-for-Life Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to exile in
France.
   Manigat met four hours Wednesday with the army general staff,
headed by Namphy, and obtained a statement from the staff pledging
allegiance to civilian rule and ``tentatively'' accepting Manigat's
decision to overrule Namphy's transfer of Paul.
   Manigat's decree Friday said that despite their pledge on
Wednesday, Namphy and other members of the general staff began to
execute the order retiring and transferring officers.
   It said their action ``is a sort of insubordination ... toward
the constitutional commander in chief.''
   The communique said all Cabinet members endorsed Manigat's
action, including Defense Minister Williams Regala, who was the
other military member with Namphy on the junta.
</TEXT>
