<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Cambodia     06-18 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Cambodia,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khmer Rouge Seize Vietnamese Border Outpost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Khmer Rouge guerrillas,
backed by mortar fire, have captured a Vietnamese defense outpost
near the Thai-Cambodian border after three days of fighting, Thai
sources said today.
   The sources, who monitored the fighting from the key Thai border
town of Aranyaprathet, said the guerrillas first attacked
Vietnamese forces opposite the Thai village of Baan Phansuek on
Wednesday.
   The Vietnamese attempted to repulse the attackers with artillery
and mortar fire but were outnumbered by the Khmer Rouge who seized
the outpost Friday, the sources said.
   The fighting occured while Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Co
Thach and his Thai counterpart Siddhi Savetsila met in Bangkok to
discuss ways to end the 9-year-old conflict in Cambodia. Both
expressed optimism that a political solution could be found.
Neither wants to see the Khmer Rouge return to power in Cambodia.
   The sources said the Vietnamese were moving artillery to a
hilltop near the scene of the fighting and might attempt to
recapture the outpost.
   Col. Chainarong Noonpakdee, deputy commander of the Burapa
(Eastern) Field Force said in a telephone interview that no
fighting was reported today. He said he could not confirm that the
Vietnamese position had fallen to the guerrillas.
   Some artillery and mortar rounds from the fighting landed inside
Thailand, forcing the evacuation of about 350 villagers living
along the frontier, the officer said.
   Chainarong said Thai troops guarding the border responded by
firing warning shots into Cambodia.
   The Khmer Rouge are the strongest of three Cambodian guerrilla
groups fighting Vietnamese forces who invaded Cambodia in late
1978. A Vietnamese offensive in late 1984 and early 1985 wiped out
the major guerrilla bases along the Thai-Cambodian border and the
three groups have since reverted to small unit, insurgency-style
warfare.
   The Khmer Rouge ruled Cambodia from 1975 until Vietnam invaded
it in late 1978. The ultra-leftist group killed millions of
Cambodians during its rule, pushing a radical brand of agrarian
communism.
</TEXT>
