<HEAD>Cubans Broadcasting on Two Frequencies Used by U.S. Radio Stations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission says it
knows the Cuban government is broadcasting at night on two AM radio
frequencies used by U.S. stations but the panel hasn't gotten any
complaints.
   The FCC said Friday the Cubans, who began the broadcast Thursday
night announced they would continue broadcasting through Sunday
night on the frequencies as part of a music festival.
   The panel said the Cubans did the same thing a year ago but the
National Association of Broadcasters said the transmissions were
``clearly a show of force'' in response to the Senate
Appropriations Committee approval Thursday of $7.5 million to start
a U.S. government TV service to Cuba to supplement Radio Marti,
which has been broadcasting to the communist-run nation for three
years.
</TEXT>
