<HEAD>All-Male Club To Vote Again On Admitting Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the all-male Cosmos Club are
scheduled to vote this afternoon for the third time in its 110-year
history on whether to admit women.
   The leadership of the club, whose members once included Supreme
Court Justices Oliver Wendell Holmes and Louis D. Brandeis, has
unanimously endorsed the idea.
   Club President Tedson J. Meyers said the question of admitting
women has become the main topic of conversation among members, but
no one will predict how the vote will come out.
   `It's a matter the club would have taken up in any event,'' said
Meyers on Friday, denying that today's vote is a direct result of a
ruling last fall by the Washington Human Rights Office that ``there
is probable cause to believe'' that the club's men-only policy
violates the city's anti-discrimination law.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Murdoch Asks FCC Permission To Put Boston TV Station in
Independent Trust</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media magnate Rupert Murdoch has proposed
putting his Boston UHF television station in an independent trust
to meet a June 30 deadline that he comply with government rules
limiting ownership of newspaper and television stations in the same
city.
   Murdoch, who owns WFXT-TV and the Boston Herald had said he
would sell the TV station but said Friday he had decided instead to
avail himself of the trust option allowed by the Federal
Communications Commission as a method of complying with the
cross-ownership rule.
   Lawrence Kessler, general counsel of Murdoch's company, News
America Publishing Inc., said the trust was chosen because ``it
seemed a more appropriate thing to do right now. It lets us remain
the beneficiary of what we believe will be a valuable property.''
   Under terms of the trust agreement, Murdoch would relinquish
control of the station but would still receive profits from the
trust which he proposed be be managed by former Sen. Edward Brooke
of Massachusetts and former New York Gov. Hugh Carey.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senate Passes Biotechnology Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has passed a bill that experts
believe is the beginning of a multibillion dollar project to map
the human genetic pattern.
   The Biotechnology Competitiveness Act passed the Senate Friday
88-1, with Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., casting the lone
dissenting vote.
   Richard D. Godown, president of the Industrial Biotechnology
Association, said the 88 to 1 vote ``shows the overwhelming support
of the United States for the biotechnology industry.''
   Although the bill doesn't authorize the start of any laboratory
research, it sets a framework for what experts believe may be a $3
billion project that could begin in two years.
   The bill's four major provisions establishes a 20-member
national policy board to review federal research support efforts
and to make recommendations on biotechnology issues, establishes an
advisory panel to develop a strategy needed for a project to map
and sequence the human genetic pattern, establishes a $10 million
biotechnology information center at the National Library of
Medicine and would reauthorize a biomedical ethics board that would
analyze the reports of the other two panels.
</TEXT>
