<DOCNO> AP880618-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 0412EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Trotsky     06-18 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Trotsky,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historian Urges Trotsky Be Exonerated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent historian said famed revolutionary
Leon Trotsky should be exonerated along with other leaders falsely
accused and purged in the early years of the Soviet state.
   ``We have to rehabilitate all those people who were repressed
and who were accused on false evidence, and all those accused must
be rehabilitated,'' Yuri Afanasyev said Friday. ``And in line with
those people is Trotsky.''
   Afanasyev, in one of the boldest proposals to date since leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev undertook his ``glasnost'' campaign for
greater openness, also called for publication in the Soviet Union
of Trotsky's banned works.
   Exonerating Trotsky of criminal charges would be another major
step toward the rehabilitation of early Soviet leaders who were
purged and killed by Kremlin leader Josef Stalin.
   Publishing Trotsky's work and revoking the criminal charges
against him would continue an intensifying campaign against the
legacy of Stalin, who died in 1953.
   It could also lead to reexamination of the key role that Trotsky
played in the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution, creating the Red Army and
leading the Communists to victory against counterrevolutionaries in
the ensuing Russian Civil War.
   That might lead Soviet historians to reevaluate the role played
by Vladmir I. Lenin, the founder of the Soviet state, who relied
heavily on Trotsky during the early years of Bolshevik rule.
   The Soviets have already taken several steps in this direction,
even publishing an article mildly critical of Lenin.
   The journal Novy Mir reported this month that Lenin was
excessively harsh in abolishing all private property, establishing
labor camps, and heavily taxing peasants. The article said Lenin
later saw that he was wrong.
   Following Lenin's death in 1924, Stalin defeated Trotsky in a
power struggle, forcing him out of the Communist Party in 1927 and
out of the Soviet Union two years later.
   Trotsky was accused of leading an anti-Soviet plot and was
murdered in Mexico City in 1940, reportedly on Stalin's orders.
   Until last fall, Trotsky was a ``non-person'' in the Soviet
Union, his writings and works universally condemned.
   Asked whether the works of Trotsky and former Soviet leader
Nikita Khrushchev might be published soon, Afanasyev answered:
   ``I can speak on behalf on myself and think they should be
republished and accessible for all ... I think it's very strange
when professors and teachers try to criticize Trotsky while they
haven't read a single word by Trotsky,'' Afanasyev told a news
conference at the Foreign Ministry press center.
   Afanasyev said that exonerating Trotsky of criminal charges and
publishing his books would not constitute an endorsement of his
ideas, which are out of line with the more liberal policies of
Gorbachev.
   Trotsky, born Lev Bronstein, was the son of a prosperous Jewish
farmer. He helped direct the coup that brought the Bolsheviks to
power, then became commissar for foreign affairs and later war,
creating and commanding the Red Army.
   He is known as the main advocate of the ``Theory of Permanent
Revolution,'' which held that the Bolshevik Revolution was a
prelude to class uprisings throughout Europe.
   After the death of Lenin, Stalin rallied his forces under the
slogan of ``Socialism in One Country,'' arguing that a socialist
state could be created in the Soviet Union, despite the failure of
revolutions elsewhere in Europe.
   Trotsky also advocated raising capital for building up industry
at the expense of the peasants. Stalin, at that time, called for
leniency against the peasants, backing a policy authored by Nikolai
Bukharin and supported by the two other leading Bolsheviks, Lev
Kamenev and Gregory Zinoviev.
   Trotsky was feared by his rivals for his skills as an orator and
organizer, his popularity among youth and his support in the Red
Army.
   Following the defeat of Trotsky, Stalin switched tactics, and
together with Kamenev and Zinoviev, began forced collectivization
of agriculture from 1929 to 1932, causing a famine and costing the
lives of millions of peasants.
   Stalin later had Bukharin, Kamenev and Zinoviev tried, sentenced
and executed in the purges of 1936-37.
   Bukharin, whose ideas are similar to those advocated by
Gorbachev, was exonerated of criminal charges in February, as were
Kamenev and Zinoviev on Monday.
   The Soviet Supreme Court on Monday also exonerated Karl Radek
and Gregory Pyatakov, who were convicted in 1937 of plotting with
Trotsky against Stalin.
   The exoneration of Radek and Pyatakov raised the possibility
that Trotsky might receive similar treatment. None of those
exonerated would be fully rehabilitated until their party
membership was restored.
   Gorbachev, in a major speech Nov. 2, became the first Soviet
leader in decades to mention Trotsky publicly, but he condemned
Trotsky's call for world revolution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880618-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 0516EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BayouDrugRing     06-18 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bayou Drug Ring,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds: International Drug Smugglers Linked To Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International drug smugglers linked to
Panamanian strongman Manuel Noriega conspired to import more than
$1 billion worth of cocaine and marijuana into the United States, a
federal indictment charges.
   The 25-count indictment unsealed Friday at Lafayette police
headquarters accused 170 people of smuggling 500,000 pounds of
drugs, some of it through south Louisiana, and with plotting to
smuggle in at least another million pounds.
   The total value of the drugs involved was placed at more than $1
billion, and U.S. Attorney Joe Cage called it perhaps the largest
U.S. narcotic smuggling ring ever. He said the organization planned
to ``flood'' the United States with illicit drugs.
   ``Its sole motivation, greed and money, caused its scope and
influence to transcend local, national and international
boundaries,'' Cage said.
   Friday's charges were a spinoff from the same federal
investigation that resulted in the indictment of Noriega on charges
that he laundered U.S. drug money through Panamanian banks, said
lawyers involved in the case.
   The Louisiana indictments disclosed that that Noriega allegedly
laundered profits from the sale of marijuana shipped to a Louisiana
shipyard.
   Had Noriega not been indicted on drug charges in Florida, he
probably would have been here, said the attorney for the federal
task force that coordinated the multistate investigation.
   ``I can't speak for a grand jury but, in my opinion, there would
have been sufficient evidence for an indictment (of Noriega),''
said Judith Lombardino, lawyer for the federal Organized Crime Drug
Enforcement Task Force.
   Also Friday, a federal grand jury in Denver indicted a purported
Colombian drug lord, Pablo Emilio Escobar-Gaviria, identified as a
principal in the Medellin drug cartel of Medellin, Colombia.
   The five-count indictment alleges that Escobar-Gaviria, 39, and
five others planned to ship up to 800 kilograms of cocaine a week
into the Denver area. Authorities estimated that amount of cocaine
could have a street value of up to $17 million.
   Escobar also is under federal indictment in Florida on charges
of conspiracy to import and distribute drugs, said U.S. Attorney
Michael J. Norton.
   Sixty-five of those charged in the 131-page Louisiana indictment
were identified as ``John Doe,'' and Cage would not say if the
indictment had connections with the Medellin Cartel, thought to be
responsible for much of the cocaine sold in the United States.
   Several arrests were made, but Cage refused to say how many. Nor
would he identify any of those indicted as ringleaders, saying each
played ``a vital role in the success of the organization.''
   The charges resulted from a 2{-year-old federal investigation
that stretched into Florida, North Carolina and Michigan, Cage said.
   About 500,000 pounds of marijuana was imported to and
distributed from Lafayette and several thousand pounds of cocaine
was flown to Shreveport, he said.
   The indictment also said 280,000 pounds of the marijuana entered
through the south Louisiana region known as Acadiana.
   The indictment said 250,000 pounds of Colombian marijuana was
seized on June 18, 1983, aboard a barge in the Vermilion Parish
community of Bancker. An additional 30,000 pounds of marijuana was
seized a few days later at a nearby house, Cage said.
   The indictment said the plan was to unload the drugs at the
Intracoastal Drydock and Shipbuilding Co., owned and operated by
the Faciane family of Abbeville. William E. Faciane and James C.
Faciane were among those indicted, Cage said.
   ``This organization schemed to flood this country and its people
with illegal drugs,'' he said. ``It is sophisticated,
well-orchestrated and rivals any multinational corporation.
   The information that led to the Louisiana indictments also led
to 82 federal indictments earlier in Florida, North Carolina and
Michigan, Cage said. Among those 82 was Noriega.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
