<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh     06-18 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tribal Rebels Reportedly Kidnap Five Traders Before Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tribal rebels kidnapped five businessmen
as the government prepared to re-open efforts to end an 11-year-old
bush war that has claimed 4,000 lives, military sources said today.
   The rebels, who are Buddhists from the Chakma tribe, abducted
the five traders at gunpoint Thursday and Friday in the Chittagong
Hill Tracts about 200 miles southeast of Dhaka, according to the
sources who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Chakmas want autonomy for their ancestral homeland near the
Indian border and resent government efforts to send settlers to the
hill tracts. Most of the settlers are Bengali-speaking Moslems.
   The kidnapped traders, who were identified only as
Bengali-speakers, were abducted in the border towns of Dighinala
and Mahalchari in the Khagrachari district.
   The military sources, who were contacted in Khagrachari, said
the rebels had killed nearly 80 people in the district since
January. In addition, they have kidnapped more than 50 fishermen
and about 10 woodcutters in the district in the last three months.
   The Bangladeshi government has no figures on the numbers of
rebels killed, but Chakma leaders across the border in India claim
2,000 of their people have disappeared. In 1987, Amnesty
International said there were ``increasing reports of arbitrary
arrests, torture and extrajudicial executions'' of tribespeople by
Bangladeshi troops in the Chittagong Hill Tracts.
   Meanwhile, state-run Radio Bangladesh said government officials
would meet Sunday with members of the Chittagong Hill Tracts'
People's Solidarity Association to renew efforts to end the bush
war. The association has been serving as a mediator in talks
between the government and the rebels.
   Peace talks broke off in April when the rebels refused to give
up their demands for autonomy and when the government refused to
let India supervise the repatriation of tribal refugees who fled
across the border to India.
   In the last two years, more than 50,000 tribespeople have fled
to the Indian state of Tripura to escape the fighting.
   The hill tracts have a population of about 600,000 tribespeople,
most of whom are Chakmas, and about 300,000 Moslem settlers.
</TEXT>
