<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Cambodia     06-18 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Cambodia,270</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chinese government has told the United
States it would be willing to offer Cambodian guerrilla leader Pol
Pot and his top aides permanent asylum in an effort reach a
poltical settlement to end the nine-year conflict in the Southeast
Asian nation, according to a published report.
   The Washington Post reported in Saturday's editions that U.S.
sources said private statements by Chinese officials, as recently
as last week at an unnannounced meeting with the country's new
foreign minister Qian Qichen at the United Nations, have indicated
the shift in posture toward Pol Pot and the Khmer Rouge.
   The sources told the newpaper the Chinese, who have provided
military aid to the Khmer Rouge, have not discussed the specifics
of Pol Pot's removal from Cambodia, where in China he and his aides
would be settled or when the government in Beijing would halt its
aid to the guerrillas.
   The reported discusssions represent the first time the Chinese
have indicated they are ready to move away from their ``bleed
Vietnam'' campaign to accepting a political settlement in the
region.
   The issue of the Khmer Rouge, blamed for the deaths of 1 million
to 2 million Cambodians during their rule in Phnom Penh from 1975
to 1978, has been an obstacle to settlment of the war in Cambodia.
   U.S. officials said the Reagan administration has not made a
decision on a Soviet request to join it as an international
``guarantor'' of a Cambodia deal. But the Cambodian issue may be
the top agenda item when the six foreign ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations meet with Secretary of State
George Shultz in Bangkok July 6-9 the ambassadors told the
newspaper.
