<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     06-18 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scenic poster sent to thousands of
business leaders promoting Florida's sunny, sultry beaches wasn't
exactly picture perfect.
   The state Division of Economic Development's poster shows a pier
and sailboat and the kind of sunset found only in Florida. Er, make
that California.
   Turns out the picture used for Florida's ad campaign actually
was shot in Manhattan Beach, Calif.
   ``Obviously it's embarrassing,'' said division director Steve
Mayberry. ``We intended for this to be a Florida shot.''
   The mistake was noticed by a California newspaper reporter who
said he was getting phone calls about the poster. KCBS-TV in Los
Angeles tracked it down and made a video of the real pier in nearby
Manhattan Beach.
   ``It's the spitting image,'' CBS-Florida reporter Dick Kane said.
   The state saved several thousand dollars by using an advertising
agency's stock photo instead of hiring a photographer to shoot a
picture for the poster, Mayberry said.
   ``They changed account executives and somewhere in the process
we didn't make sure that this picture was taken in Florida,''
Mayberry said.
   The idea of the poster was to ``keep our name before these
corporate executives to let them know that one of the advantages we
have here in Florida is gorgeous weather and a gorgeous
lifestlyle,'' Mayberry said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATASCADERO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kris Johnson got more than a diploma
at her high school graduation ceremony.
   She got a marriage proposal, printed on a banner that fluttered
behind a plane as it buzzed over the ceremony Thursday. It read,
``Kris. I love you. Please Marry Me! Den.''
   Miss Johnson, 18, sitting in the third row with her classmates,
said yes and flung herself into the arms of her boyfriend, Denny
Peters, 22, who bolted across the lawn to hug her during his aerial
proposal Thursday.
   Miss Johnson smothered him with kisses and yeses, much to the
delight of the crowd, which had been sitting solemnly during the
commencement speech but went wild with applause during the proposal.
   ``I wasn't romantic until I met her,'' said Peters, who paid
$200 for the plane message. ``She brings it out in me. The person
you love the most should know it the most, at least in the grandest
style.''
</TEXT>
