<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 0506EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Slavery     06-18 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Slavery,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>66 People Arrested For Trafficking In Teenage Girls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have broken a nationwide ring
trafficking in teenage girls, arresting 66 people involved in
kidnapping and selling more than 200 girls into slavery, an
official report said today.
   The girls, most of whom were abducted at train stations, were
raped before they were sold, the Peasants Daily said.
   Authorities were in the process of locating and freeing the
girls, the report said.
   They were tipped off in November 1987 when a 17-year-old girl
identified her abductor, but the report did not say when the
arrests were made.
   The ring was based in Zhengzhou, a transportation center in
Henan province, in central China, but operated throughout central,
southern and western China, covering more than 20 provinces, the
report said.
   Members of the well-organized operation were responsible for
specific tasks, including management, sales, communications and
abducting the ``goods,'' the paper said.
   The girls were given code names, depending on which part of the
country they came from, how they were abducted or their marital
status.
   Girls who were married were called ``white goods,'' those who
were single were referred to as ``yellow goods.''
   The girls were fooled into thinking their abductors would find
them a job or wanted them to be their adopted sisters or daughters,
the report said.
   A 15-year-old girl who ran away from home after fighting with
her parents, was picked up at the railroad station in Xian, Shanxi
province, raped and sold to Anhui province. She was later resold
for $730, it said.
   Two girls from Sichuan province, one 15 years old and the other
16, were on their way home after visiting relatives in Zhengzhou
when they were abducted at the Zhengzhou railway station. One was
sold for $810, the other for $946, the paper said.
   All three girls were severely beaten by their owners and
forbidden to leave the house.
   The report quoted an officer of the Zhengzhou Public Security
Bureau as saying that while the crimes were not the direct result
of China's reform policies, they were caused by economic reforms
that have forced peasants to leave the farm and forced workers out
of jobs.
   He also criticized the peasants who bought the girls for their
ignorance of the law. He said when authorities went to free a girl
in Shandong province, angry peasants tried to stop them, saying,
``We don't steal, we don't rob. We used our own money to buy a
girl. What's wrong with that?''
</TEXT>
