<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham     06-18 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Says He's Vindicated, May Run For Office Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLENDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham, cleared of
criminal charges that he tried to hide a campaign loan, says he's
considering a new bid for the post he lost to a Senate impeachment
conviction.
   ``That one (the governorship) will come up in 1990 and yes,
that's certainly an option,'' Mecham told reporters Friday, adding
there also was ``always a chance'' of a campaign this year for U.S.
Senate or Congress.
   A jury on Thursday acquittted Mecham and his brother, Willard,
on criminal charges of concealing the $350,000 campaign loan.
   The 64-year-old Republican was removed from office April 4 when
the state Senate convicted him of two unrelated impeachment counts.
   Mecham told reporters after the verdict that he had no
vindictive feelings. But he accused Attorney General Bob Corbin of
abusing his office and vowed to support a petition drive to recall
the prosecutor.
   ``We went through eight months of misery'' after Corbin's
investigation of the campaign loan began last fall, Mecham said.
``Thank God those jurors could see through the accusations and get
to the facts.''
   The former governor also accused a Court of Appeals judge _ whom
he did not name _ of ruling on an appeal in his criminal case
despite having ``openly declared that I was dishonest and should be
in jail.''
   Mecham's attorney, Michael Scott, said a complaint might be
filed with the state Bar Association's judicial ethics committee.
   Willard Mecham, his brother's 1986 campaign treasurer, said
testifying before state grand juries was ``by far the most evil
experiences I have ever had. The perjury in this case was committed
by the state attorneys who prosecuted us.''
   Evan Mecham said he felt vindicated ``on the legal issues, but
justice in the political arena will take a little longer.''
   Mecham said his political action committee, Forward Arizona,
will work to elect a Legislature ``that represents the people, and
not the hidden power brokers.''
   He said the group will consider starting an alternative
newspaper to counter what he views as a biased Phoenix press. Plans
are in the works for two books, a TV movie and a feature film, he
said, joking that he would like to be portrayed by actor Clint
Eastwood.
   He said his legal defense cost about $550,000, almost half of
which has been contributed by supporters.
   During a news conference at his private office, Mecham was
jubilant while his brother often appeared on the verge of tears.
Afterward, Mecham cut a cake that said ``Truth Prevails _ Evan and
Willard.''
   Mecham was prosecuted for failing to itemize the $350,000
campaign loan from attorney-developer Barry Wolfson on either his
personal or campaign finance reports.
   The defense contended the loan was properly reported as part of
a $465,000 lump sum listed as a contribution from Mecham, and that
the failure to itemize it was an innocent mistake by Willard Mecham.
   Mecham was acquitted of all six charges of perjury, willful
concealment and filing false documents. His brother was acquitted
of three similar counts.
</TEXT>
