<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Uranus-Challenger     06-18 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Uranus-Challenger,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Astronomers Reject Naming Uranian Moons After Challenger's Crew</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of scientists has recommended naming
the moons of Uranus after the literary characters of William
Shakespeare and Alexander Pope rather than the crew killed when the
space shuttle Challenger exploded.
   ``We're following the tradition of naming the moons after
Shakespearean characters and characters from (Alexander Pope's)
`The Rape of the Lock,''' said U.S. Geological Survey planetary
geologist Hal Masursky, who chairs the International Astronomical
Union's planetary system nomenclature working group.
   ``It wasn't intended to be a slight'' to the thousands of
schoolchildren, citizens and officials who wrote letters and signed
petitions proposing naming the moons for the astronauts, Brian
Marsden, director of the IAU's Central Bureau for Astronomical
Telegrams, said Friday.
   He said seven asteroids were named for Challenger astronauts two
months after the shuttle exploded after liftoff Jan. 28, 1986. The
IAU also will name seven lunar craters for Francis Scobee, Michael
J. Smith, Judith Resnik, Ronald McNair, Ellison Onizuka, Gregory
Jarvis and teacher-astronaut Sharon Christa McAuliffe, he said.
   Uranus has 15 known moons, 10 of which were discovered in
December 1985 and January 1986 by NASA's Voyager 2 spacecraft. The
probe's triumphant Jan. 24, 1986, close encounter with Uranus was
overshadowed by the Challenger tragedy.
   Marsden said the IAU's executive committee decided in a private
meeting in San Diego last September to endorse the proposal by
Masursky's working group to name nine new moons for Shakespearean
characters _ Juliet, Puck, Bianca, Cordelia, Cressida, Desdemona,
Ophelia, Rosalind and Portia. The 10th will be named after Belinda,
whose lock of hair was stolen in ``The Rape of the Lock.''
   The IAU general assembly is certain to rubber-stamp the proposal
on the last day of its Aug. 2-11 meeting in Baltimore, Md., Marsden
said.
   ``Astronomers feel that even though the moons were discovered by
the United States, the satellites really are international,
therefore going along with tradition would have international
acceptance,'' Marsden said by phone from Cambridge, Mass.
   ``Naming features or moons is not the property of any one
country,'' Masursky said.
   Of Uranus' five previously known moons, Oberon, Titania and
Miranda are Shakespearean names, Umbriel is from Pope's poem, while
Ariel is a name found in both ``The Rape of the Lock'' and
Shakespeare's ``The Tempest,'' Marsden said.
   The craters to be named for Challenger's crew measure 20 to 60
miles wide and are located ``in an enormous crater named Apollo on
the far side of the moon,'' Masursky said by phone from Flagstaff,
Ariz.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880618-0027 </DOCNO>
