<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Italy-Bombs     06-18 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Bombs,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Bombs Explode In Ethnically Troubled Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOLZANO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs exploded today in this capital
of an ethnically troubled province near the Austrian border. The
blasts broke windows but injured no one, police said.
   The blasts came the day after Parliament gave final approval to
a new agreement granting more autonomy and other benefits to the
German-speaking residents of Alto Adige, or South Tyrol, in
northern Italy. The region was part of Austria until the end of
World War I.
   Police said the first bomb exploded before dawn in front of the
courthouse, and the second a few minutes later on a street in an
Italian-speaking neighborhood. Authorities said both were hidden in
trash cans.
   On May 17, four bombs exploded in this city before a meeting in
Vienna where Austria approved the agreement. There were no
casualties from those explosions.
   Police blamed them on German-speaking extremists who want
self-determination for the region. There was no immediate word on
who may have planted the bombs that went off today, though police
noted that one bomb went off in the Italian-speaking area.
   Austria has long championed rights of German-speaking residents
in the area. Terrorist attacks in the 1960s led to an agreement
between Italy and Austria establishing the rights and privileges of
ethnic groups.
</TEXT>
