<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CyanideDeaths     06-18 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyanide Deaths,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Convicted In Tampering Case Sentenced To 90 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Murder charges could be filed against Stella
Nickell, who was sentenced to 90 years in prison for the
``exceptional callousness and cruelty'' of putting cyanide in
pain-relief capsules that killed her husband and a stranger two
years ago.
   King County Prosecutor Norm Maleng said he had waited until the
sentencing Friday to start a review of whether state murder charges
would be filed against Mrs. Nickell.
   Maleng said state laws against double jeopardy are stricter than
the U.S. Constitution's protection, but it was possible the state
murder law and federal anti-product tampering statute differ enough
to allow prosecution.
   At the sentencing, U.S. District Judge William Dwyer harshly
criticized Mrs. Nickell for the severity of her crimes.
   ``The jury has found the defendant guilty of appalling crimes,''
said Dwyer, who recommended Mrs. Nickell, 44, of suburban Auburn
not be eligible for parole for at least 30 years.
   It will not be the first time behind bars for Mrs. Nickell. She
spent six months in jail after she violated probation in Orange
County, Calif., on a 1971 conviction for check fraud.
   Then known as Stella Strong, she also was convicted of child
beating in Southern California in 1969. It could not be determined
immediately what sentence she received.
   The victim of the beating was her daughter, Cindy Hamilton, now
28, who was the key witness in Mrs. Nickell's product-tampering
trial.
   Mrs. Nickell, the first person brought to trial under a federal
law dealing with death by product tampering, appeared pale and
unsmiling Friday, but did not otherwise respond when Dwyer
sentenced her. She made no statement in court.
   Her attorney, Thomas Hillier, told Dwyer she maintains her
innocence and would appeal her conviction.
   ``It must be said that these are crimes of exceptional
callousness and cruelty,'' Dwyer said, noting that poisoned
capsules had been left on store shelves and could easily have lead
to other deaths.
   Mrs. Nickell, convicted May 9, received 90-year terms on each of
two counts of product tampering, which killed her husband, Bruce
Nickell, and Susan Katherine Snow, also of Auburn.
   She also was sentenced to 10-year terms on each of three
tampering counts for poisoning bottles of Extra-Strength Excedrin
and Anacin found in the Nickell home and on the shelves of area
stores.
   All terms were to run concurrently. In addition, Dwyer levied a
mandatory $250 minimum fine and said any of Mrs. Nickell's assets
should be used to compensate her victims, especially Mrs. Snow's
family.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joanne Maida, the prosecutor in the
case, said Mrs. Nickell was indigent and the compensation issue was
``academic.''
   Prosecutors had requested a 230-year sentence, with a minimum 67
years before parole eligibility, saying entire families could have
died because of the tampering.
   Prosecutors alleged Mrs. Nickell killed her husband because she
was tired of him and wanted to collect $176,000 in life insurance.
They said Mrs. Snow, who had no connection with the couple, was an
innocent victim of a plot to make Nickell's death appear the work
of a random killer.
   The deaths set off a nationwide tampering scare and caused
Excedrin manufacturer Bristol-Myers Co. to recall its
non-prescription capsule medicines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880618-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 0744EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HospitalRules     06-18 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Rules,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>HHS Warns Hospitals Not To ``Dump'' Patients Who Can't Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal health officials are proposing new
regulations that would impose fines and other penalties on
hospitals that turn away emergency room patients for fear they
can't afford to pay.
   A letter sent to hospital administrators states that when a
patient comes to an emergency room, the hospital must offer
``appropriate medical screening examinations to all individuals
with emergency medical conditions and all women in active labor.''
   ``They may either stabilize the condition or provide a medically
appropriate transfer to another facility when indicated, unless the
patient or their legal representative refuses treatment or
transfer,'' it says.
   The letter was sent by Health and Humans Services Inspector
General Richard P. Kusserow, Medicare administrator William L.
Roper and Office for Civil Rights Director Audrey F. Morton.
   The proposed new rules were published this week in the Federal
Register and will become law after a period of public comment.
   The letter warns that violating the law by refusing to accept
emergency room patients can result in penalties of up to $50,000,
civil lawsuits under state laws, and suspension or exclusion from
the Medicare program.
   The rules cover all patients, not just those on Medicare.
   Congress enacted legislation in 1986 to guard against instances
in which hospitals were turning away women in labor and other
patients in need of immediate care because they did not have money
or insurance to pay for medical services.
</TEXT>
