<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 0754EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DriftingBoat     06-18 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drifting Boat,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Costa Rican Fishermen Arrive on Land After Five Months Adrift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Costa Rican fishermen kept from going crazy
during five months adrift in a 30-foot boat by fishing, praying and
remembering their families back home, one of them says.
   ``We tried to keep ourselves busy, and that helped a lot,''
Gerardo Obregon Obando, captain of the fishing boat Cairo III, said
Friday. ``We were grateful no one took a knife and tried to kill
somebody.''
   ``We fished, we prayed, we put our faith in God. We never gave
up hope.''
   A Japanese tuna boat spotted Obando and his crew 700 miles
southeast of here Wednesday and brought them to Oahu on Friday.
Obando said the Cairo III set out Jan. 19 from Puntarenas, Costa
Rica, for an eight-day fishing trip, but was driven from land by a
storm and ran out of gas before it could reach port.
   The boat and its crew drifted 3,600 miles across the Pacific
Ocean, according to Coast Guard spokesman Jeff Crawley.
   Obando, 33, the only crewman who agreed to be interviewed, said
the five collected rainwater and caught enough food to stay healthy.
   ``We lived on sharks, fish _ even little fish _ and whatever
else got near the boat,'' Obando said through an interpreter. ``We
had containers which we had ready all the time to catch rainwater.''
   Dr. Martha Hauk of the Coast Guard, who examined the men before
they left the Kinei Maru 128, said she was surprised to find them
in near-perfect health.
   ``They just look so good it's amazing,'' she said.
   Doctors at Tripler Army Medical Center also examined the men and
said the five were in good shape and none would be hospitalized,
said hospital spokesman George Vidis. Two of them were treated for
mild dehydration and one was treated for an abscessed tooth, he
said.
   Obando said the storm struck Jan. 24 while the boat was three or
four hours from shore.
   The storm, which Obando said lasted more than two weeks, knocked
out the Cairo III's radio and the vessel's motor failed in rough
seas. The boat ran out of fuel while trying to reach land after the
storm broke.
   Supplies ran out after eight days at sea, Obando said. They
never went hungry, but they went one or two days without water.
``We were so thirsty we were licking the sides of the containers,''
he said.
   The crew fashioned a small, makeshift sail that helped them move
with the current, Obando said.
   Hilda Richardson, the Costa Rican consul in Hawaii, said the men
would spend tonight in a hotel and probably be flown home Sunday.
   Mrs. Richardson said she had informed families in Costa Rica
that the fishermen had been found. She said the man hadn't been
able to speak with their families Friday, but probably would be
able to telephone them before leaving Honolulu.
   Tatsuo Oyama, captain of the Kinei Maru 128, said a lookout
spotted the Cairo III with the men waving on its deck. The men were
rescued, but the boat was left adrift.
   The fishermen were identified as Obando, George Fernandez
Castillo, 22, Pastor Lopez Rojas, 30, Joel Omar Gonzalez, 27, and
Juan Cernas Bolivar, 47.
   Obando said he and his crew, all from Puntarenas, would return
to fishing but first would spend time with their families.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
