<HEAD>Chlorine Fire Forces Evacuation of 6,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with residents beginning to
return home, 125 taken to hospital, other details. Picks up in 10th
graf, `The cloud ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first of 6,000 people evacuated
from neighborhoods choked by a chlorine gas cloud began returning
to their homes today after a chemical fire at a supply plant was
brought under control.
   At least 125 people were treated overnight for injuries from the
gas cloud, but none was admitted, hospital supervisors said. In
addition, 13 firefighters were treated and released for exposure to
fumes or chemical burns.
   Two high schools and a hospital were turned into shelters for
the evacuees, among them scores of nursing home residents and some
800 Methodists attending an annual weekend meeting at Springfield
College, Fire Department spokesman Giorgio Placanico said.
   ``I don't really believe it happened, even though I'm trained as
a chemist and know the dangers of chlorine,'' said Elizabeth Lurie,
55, of Leominster, as she waited to return to the dormitory room
she left just before midnight Friday.
   Fire officials said the gas cloud was still hanging over a small
section of the evacuated area today and it would be hours before
some residents could return to their homes. The fire was brought
under control at 3:15 a.m.
   Police wearing gas masks patrolled the area.
   The fire that spawned the chlorine gas cloud was one of two at
the three-story Advanced Laboratories plant Friday.
   Investigators believed the two fires were unrelated, but arson
has not been ruled out, Fire Commissioner Anthony Pellegrino said.
   A police cruiser making a routine drive through the area
reported the fire about 11 p.m., Placanico said.
   At least 100 firefighters, some wearing oxygen tanks and gas
masks, worked to extinguish the blaze.
   People were evacuated in buses from neighborhoods near the fire.
About half of those evacuated went to the three shelters, while the
others fled to the homes of relatives or friends.
   The cloud of chlorine gas had a radius of at least a half mile,
officials said.
   The first fire began shortly after 10 a.m., when rain from an
early morning thunderstorm apparently blew through an open window
onto chlorine dust and into a chlorine hopper at the plant,
sparking a chemical reaction, Sullivan said.
   Firefighters using soda ash quickly extinguished the flames, but
as the fumes began to spread in the hot, muggy air, authorities
evacuated all homes, businesses and schools within a quarter mile
of the plant as a precautionary measure, he said. Residents were
allowed to return two hours later, before being evacuated again
Friday night.
</TEXT>
