<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Election,2nd Ld - Writethru, a0427,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gandhi Foe Takes Strong Lead In Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE vote totals and include Ghandi
quote; picks up 5th graf pvs: About 850,000...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Minister V.P. Singh
boosted his chances of opposing Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi in
national elections by taking a commanding lead today in a
parliamentary election.
   With 70.5 percent of the ballots counted from Thursday's special
election in the Allahabad district, Singh had 54 percent to 24
percent for his nearest challenger, singer and film writer Sunil
Shastri.
   Shastri, son of the late Prime Minister Lal Bahadur Shastri, was
the candidate of Gandhi's Congress Party. Singh ran as an
independent with the backing of several opposition parties.
   By early evening today, the 56-year-old Singh had 163,058 of the
300,000 votes counted. Shastri, 38, had 71,868. The rest were
divided among 66 other candidates.
   Gandhi was quoted by Indian news agency reporters as saying that
the election results were not unexpected.
   ``The ruling party gets it in its neck'' in off-year elections,
Gandhi was quoted as saying. ``The Congress is satisfied over the
outcome of the polls as it has come at a difficult time.''
   About 850,000 people were eligible to vote, but election workers
estimated only about 50 percent turned out.
   The Allahabad contest was one of seven special parliamentary
elections conducted Thursday. By this morning, the Congress Party
had captured one seat and opposition parties had two.
   Votes were still being counted in three other constituencies,
including Allahabad. In the seventh district, in Haryana state, the
count has not begun because of reports of ballot-stuffing.
   In state legislative elections also conducted Thursday, the
Congress Party took five seats and opposition parties won five.
Vote-counting was stayed in an 11th contest in Haryana state
because of the ballot-stuffing charges.
   The contest in Allahabad, 360 miles southeast of New Delhi,
provided the first voter test of Singh's ability to oppose Prime
Minister Gandhi for the leadership of the nation.
   Under its constitution, India must conduct national elections no
later than January 1990.
   Singh, who campaigned on an anti-corruption platform, was a
member of Gandhi's Congress Party until last summer when he broke
with the prime minister and quit the Cabinet over the government's
hesitation to investigate corruption.
   As defense minister, Singh wanted to look into allegations that
kickbacks were paid to purchase Bofors artillery guns from Sweden
and submarines from West Germany.
   According to Indian press reports, the kickbacks were paid to
government officials and friends of Gandhi. Gandhi himself was
never accused of wrongdoing, and a parliamentary report later said
it had uncovered no irregularities.
</TEXT>
