<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Escape, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0443,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three of Eight Escapees Found</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with two more escapees caught
today. Picks up 10th graf, `Probation and ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDDYVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities began house-to-house searches
and stepped up checkpoints on roadways today after three of eight
escapees from the Kentucky State Penitentiary were captured near
the maximum-security prison.
   Leo Spurling, 30, and Floyd Cook, 35, were apprehended about
7:30 a.m. today near Eddyville, about two mines north of the
penitentiary, prison spokesman Don Sapienza said.
   Robert G. Sherman, 30, was captured Friday afternoon in the same
area.
   Spurling, a convicted murderer, and Cook, a convicted rapist,
were captured after authorities on foot and in cars, boats and
airplanes searched the area.
   Meanwhile, a prosecutor who sent one of the men to prison for
murder was given extra protection, and authorities reported they
found a broken hacksaw blade in a prison toilet.
   Sherman, in handcuffs, greeted prison officials upon his return
with a broad smile. He was wearing dirty black sweatpants and gray
socks but no shirt, and his heavily tatooed back was full of
scratches. A prison guard carried Sherman's boots.
   Sherman was serving 15 years for robbery, escape, wanton
endangerment and promoting contraband.
   The warden said Sherman appeared embarrassed when told he was
the first escapee caught.
   Probation and parole officers in the escapees' hometowns were
asked to check with inmates' families, relatives and acquaintances
to see if they knew of their whereabouts, Seabold said.
   Prison spokesman Barry Banister said that until confirmed
sightings were received, authorities were operating on the premise
that the escapees were still in the vicinity of the prison.
   The eight prisoners escaped early Thursday morning after they
sawed through cell doors and a barred window. Prison guards were
diverted by a fire that had been set on the floor below. The
prisoners were housed in isolation cells reserved for the
penitentiary's troublemakers.
   Prison spokesman Bobby Waller said the window almost certainly
had been broken for some time to allow prisoners access to the
outer bars. Prison officials were investigating why guards had not
reported the broken window earlier, Waller said.
   The century-old prison remained under a lockdown Friday, with
the other 770 prisoners allowed out of their cells only for meals.
   Reporters on Friday were given their first look at the No. 3
cellhouse, from which the prisoners escaped.
   Seventeen of the 160 cell doors were disabled in the escape,
said Jerry Merrick, the prison's chief engineer.
   Authorities found a 2- to 3-inch piece of a hacksaw in one of
the escapee's toilets Thursday, and an attempt had been made to
flush it, Waller said.
   ``There's no doubt in my mind that they used a hacksaw blade in
order to cut out,'' Waller said Friday.
   Meanwhile, ``extra security measures'' were put into effect for
Jefferson County Commonwealth's Attorney Ernest Jasmin, said his
first assistant, John W. Stewart. He declined to detail the
measures, and said they were ``nothing to suggest we're afraid, but
better safe than sorry.''
   Jasmin prosecuted Leo C. Spurling, one of four convicted murders
among the escapees. He received a life sentence.
</TEXT>
