<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Catholics     06-18 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Catholics,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholics Told Not To Celebrate Canonization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catholics in central Vietnam have been
told not to celebrate the Vatican's canonization Sunday of
Vietnamese martyrs, which Hanoi has condemned as politically
motivated, Vietnam's official Radio Hanoi said.
   Pope John Paul II is to preside over the canonization of 117
martyrs, the largest in church history, at St. Peter's Basilica in
the Vatican. Thousands of Vietnamese, many of whom fled their
communist homeland, are expected to attend and Hanoi fears it will
become a widely publicized anti-communist rally.
   The radio said Thursday that Bishop Huynh Dong Cat of Qui Nhon
diocese in central Nghia Binh province sent a June 11 letter to
priests and lay followers instructing them not to mark the occasion.
   It said Cat wrote the letter a day after the the provincial
people's committee, or government, ``invited'' him for a meeting
and outlined the official stand on the issue.
   A text of the broadcast was obtained from a Western embassy in
Bangkok today.
   The broadcast said the letter noted that Sunday also is the day
the government of South Vietnam had celebrated its army. Communists
defeated the South Vietnam government in April 1975 and reunified
Vietnam.
   The Vatican has said the timing of the ceremony is coincidental.
   The letter continued: ``On that day, you brothers and sisters
can go to churches as usual. However, you should not organize
canonization masses, hoist banners, make decorations and hold
meetings or engage in any illegal activities at your churches that
could be exploited by bad elements to disrupt public order and
security.''
   Refugees and others said that since 1975, Vietnam has closed
seminaries and taken other steps to systematically repress
Catholicism in the largely Buddhist nation. But new Vietnamese
leadership has taken steps over the past two years to allow more
religious freedom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
