<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 1541EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FireTestDeath     06-18 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fire Test Death,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ambulance Takes 40 Minutes to Reach Firefighter Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials are investigating why it took
paramedics at least 40 minutes to reach a man who collapsed, and
later died, after an endurance test for would-be firefighters.
   The grueling test, which was to have been taken by 28,000 people
seeking jobs as firefighters, has been halted indefinitely while
officials try to determine what caused Freddy Padilla to die and
seven others to become ill.
   Padilla, 24, collapsed June 11 after completing the seven-minute
test; he died seven hours after arriving at St. Luke's-Roosevelt
Medical Center. It was unclear whether a faster response by the
Emergency Medical Service might have saved his life.
   According to Magda Gandasegui, a spokeswoman for the city
Personnel Department, Padilla finished the test about 12:30 p.m. He
apparently reported feeling ill and was looked at by a fire
lieutenant, trained as an emergency medical technician, who took
his pulse and checked his breathing, she said.
   Records show that the lieutenant called EMS at 12:40 p.m. and
asked for an ambulance, according to EMS spokeswoman Donna Osso.
She said a crew arrived at 12:53 p.m. but told the EMS dispatcher
that it could not find the patient; the assignment was canceled as
unfounded.
   The record also shows that at 1:07 p.m. the lieutenant called
EMS again to ask where the ambulance was, Ms. Osso said. This time
the lieutenant told the EMS commander to send the ambulance to an
entrance to the building on West 58th Street and to ``use the
elevator entrance.''
   The EMS commander relayed the message to the EMS dispatcher, but
did not mention the elevator entrance. The dispatcher sent the same
crew.
   At 1:20 p.m., Ms. Osso said, the ambulance crew called the
dispatcher to say that they still could not find the patient.
   Sometime after that, the crew reached Padilla, who was conscious
and talking when they arrived, she said, adding there was no record
of exactly when the crew found him.
   Twenty minutes after the crew reached him, Padilla was taken to
the hospital, where he died shortly before 9 p.m., according to
Ellen Borakove, a spokeswoman for the medical examiner.
   Autopsy results were inconclusive and further tests were needed
to determine the cause of death, Ms. Borakove said.
   The other seven firefighter candidates who became ill after the
test were taken to St. Luke's-Roosevelt, where three were admitted
and two remained hospitalized in good condition Saturday, according
to hospital spokeswoman Judy Murphy.
   Ms. Murphy said the patients were treated for mild-to-moderate
kidney disorders, caused by physical exertion.
   The department began testing May 31 and was scheduled to finish
in July. More than 5,000 candidates have finished the test, Ms.
Gandasegui said.
   Candidates are required to sign a statement certifying that they
are in good physical condition, but are not required to have a
physical exam before taking the test.
   During the test, would-be firefighters, wearing 40 pounds of
gear, scale walls, carry a 145-pound dummy, break down a door and
drag 57 pounds of hose.
   ``It is not unusual for people to feel wobbly or vomit after
taking the test,'' Ms. Gandasegui said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
