<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EEC-Agriculture     06-18 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EEC-Agriculture,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greece Blocks EEC Farm Deal, Compromise Sought</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece on Friday blocked a farm-price
compromise that took European Economic Community ministers three
months to reach but officials said hopes remained that a solution
could still be found.
   The austere farm package calls for price freezes or cuts to keep
the EEC's 1988-89 farm budget within a $33.5 billion ceiling
imposed by EEC leaders at a summit last February.
   Officials said the Greek agricultural minister, Yannis Potakis,
threatened to veto the package that had been accepted by his 11 EEC
partners if Ignaz Kiechle, the West German delegate and the
meeting's chairman, put it to a vote.
   Potakis claimed a price boost for Greek farmers would not cost
the EEC budget as much as calculated and asked for higher prices
for Greek farmers.
   The EEC commission that drafted the farm budget acknowledged its
calculations might not be correct but said it could not change the
entire price scheme to which 11 countries agreed. It said other
members would ask for additional changes and thus undermine the
package.
   A new meeting may be called while the commission studies
possible concessions to Greece.
   The agriculture ministers began their meeting last Monday.
Throughout the negotiations the commission made concessions to
various demands by agreeing to a gradual dismantling of a complex
system of taxes on exports of farm produce from countries with
weaker currencies.
   Kiechle could call for another farm ministers meeting before his
six-month term as chairman expires on June 30, officials said.
</TEXT>
