<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AdultSpellingBee     06-18 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Adult Spelling Bee,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uncommon Words No Problem For Champion Speller</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SECAUCUS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who says he has difficulty with
small words like ``it'' won an adult spelling bee Saturday when he
correctly spelled ``mythopoeia.''
   ``A piece of cake,'' said 40-year-old John Marron, whose prowess
in the corporate-sponsored contest earned him and his wife a trip
to the Caribbean island of Curacao.
   Marron, a family counselor at the Association for the
Advancement of Mental Health in Princeton, said he was taught well
by nuns at a Catholic grammar school in Davenport, Iowa.
   ``We learned the phonetics of spelling,'' he said. He didn't
come across mythopoeia _ creating a myth _ until later in life,
perhaps at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore or John F. Kennedy
University in Orinda, Calif., he said.
   The New Jersey offices of the Olsten Corp., a Westbury,
N.Y.-based company that provides temporary employees, sponsored the
bee to highlight its concern about literacy in the workplace. The
company touted the adult contest as the first of its kind in the
nation.
   Marron savored his victory over 29 other finalists at the
Meadowlands Hilton and recalled the disappointment of a second
grade spelling contest.
   ``I went out on `accommodate,''' he said.
   But this time, Marron survived eight rounds and a tense
spell-off with runner-up Tim Peach, 24, of Fort Lee.
   ``I really don't have too much trouble spelling,'' Marron said.
``It's those little words like `it' that can really stump me.''
   Unlike many contestants, Marron said he did not study for the
bee but relied on his memory and several years of studying Latin,
Spanish and French to help with etymology.
   Peach, an actuarial at Kwasha Lipton in Fort Lee, lost by
misspelling `viridescent,' which means slightly green. He said he
borrowed some books by William F. Buckley from his boss to prepare
for the bee.
   ``I skimmed them for big words and there were a lot of them,''
he said.
   Peach said he expected to put the second place prize of a $2,000
scholarship toward his fiancee's education at a music school in New
York City.
   Saturday's finalists survived a first-round written phase June
11 involving representatives from about 80 corporations across the
state, many of whom had won in-house spelling bees.
</TEXT>
