<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0598 06-18 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0598,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Accuses Dukakis Of Coddling Criminals</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 1st 2 grafs to fix typo in `murderers'; SUBS 15th graf
pvs, bgng: The vice president, to restore dropped word `not'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush on Saturday
accused Democrat Michael Dukakis of being soft on criminals for
supporting a Massachusetts program letting inmates, including
murderers, out of prison on weekends.
   ``What did the Democratic governor of Massachusetts think he was
doing when he let convicted first-degree murderers out on weekend
passes?'' said Bush, the all but certain Republican presidential
nominee. ``Even after one of the criminals brutally raped a woman
and stabbed her fiance, why didn't he admit his mistake?''
   Bush, who was touring the drought-damaged Midwest, issued his
sharpest attack so far on Dukakis over the prison furlough issue.
   ``I think Gov. Dukakis owes the people of the United States an
explanation for why he supported this outrageous program,'' Bush
told the Illinois State Republican Convention.
   Bush told his audience that at least one woman was raped as a
result of the prison furlough program.
   ``Eight months later he was still defending his program,'' Bush
said of his Democratic rival for the White House. ``And only when
the Massachusetts Legislature voted by an overwhelming majority to
abolish the program for murders did he finally give in.''
   In April Dukakis signed a bill banning furloughs for
first-degree murders. The bill was prompted by a public outcry over
the rape, which occurred last year in Maryland.
   ``We don't let murderers out on vacation to terrorize innocent
people,'' Bush said.
   The Dukakis campaign accused Bush of misrepresenting the facts.
   ``George Bush should know better,'' Dukakis press secretary
Dayton Duncan said while traveling with the candidate in Texas.
``He should check the record of Ronald Reagan as (California)
governor, the federal system in his own administration and of 22
states with Republican governors before he makes more wild
accusations about furlough systems.''
   Bush, accompanied by Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng and
Illinois Gov. James Thompson, visited a drought-stricken farm,
where corn plants were parched and little more than ankle-high.
   ``We need two inches of rain before two weeks. This corn is
hurting,'' the farmer, Raymond Poe, told Bush.
   The vice president, in his shirtsleeves, sat on a bale of hay
and discussed the drought with a group of local farmers.
   ``I've learned how serious this problem is of drought and the
kind of suffering it can cause in the farm community,'' Bush said.
   But he didn't hold out much in the way of federal help.
   ``There are serious budget restraints on what the federal
government can do,'' he said.
   The vice president insisted that his farm visit _ added to the
schedule at the last minute _ was not politically motivated.
   ``That's absolutely absurd,'' he said. ``We've got a national
problem and I'm the vice president of the United States. When
agricultural America is hurting, of course we care.''
   Lyng, meanwhile, said that while the drought was clearly a
serious problem for U.S. farmers, ``a drought in an election year
is worse than a drought in a non-election year.''
   ``People overreact,'' Lyng told a group of reporters at Andrews
Air Force Base near Washington as he prepared to board Air Force
Two with Bush for the flight to Illinois.
   ``With people running for office, you get a sense of added
urgency,'' Lyng said.
   The agriculture secretary said he did not mean to imply the
drought was not a major one. ``It's a real drought,'' he said.
   Asked what measures the government might take to aid farmers,
Lyng said, ``We've tried about all we think we can do in terms of
emergency steps _ except money. And it's too early to consider
that.''
   ``What you really need is rain, and there's no way you can bring
that,'' he said.
   Thompson, speaking with reporters, said ``farmers aren't
stupid'' and wouldn't blame the drought on politicians.
   ``Farmers have coped with drought, hail, tornadoes, too much
rain, insects for years and years and years,'' Thompson said. ``The
Reagan-Bush administration has done more than any other
administration in the history of the United States to help
farmers.''
   Meanwhile, Bush told the Illinois GOP convention that ``we're
involved in a close election and unity is important.''
   He said that Republicans were more unified now than ever before.
   The vice president also repeated his call for beefing up the war
on drugs, and added a new twist.
   ``Because trade in drugs is like terrorism, we must expand our
covert activities to fight it,'' Bush said.
   Asked later what he meant by ``covert activities,'' Bush said:
``If you discuss it, it's not covert. Just let it stand. If there's
going to be a war, let's fight the war using every aspect we have.''
   Bush was also attending two fund-raising events in Chicago
before returning to Washington late Saturday.
</TEXT>
