<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-18 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little Rain Falling To End Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   There was little relief for drought areas Saturday with wet
weather extending from the Northeast into the South and rain only
scattered over the dry upper Midwest.
   During the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, the heaviest rain was
0.20 of an inch at Corpus Christi, Texas, and no other official
stations recorded over a tenth of an inch, the National Weather
Service said.
   Thunderstorms were scattered from around New York's Long Island
southwestward through the central and southern Appalachians into
parts of the lower Mississippi Valley.
   The strongest storms developed across parts of eastern Tennessee
into western parts of North and South Carolina. Hail the diameter
of dimes was reported at Horse Shoe, N.C.
   Thunderstorms also rumbled across the Florida Keys.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were scattered over parts of
southern Texas.
   Showers moved from eastern parts of Iowa into south-central
Wisconsin and showers and thunderstorms were scattered across
eastern North Dakota into northwestern Minnesota.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms moved across parts of the
desert Southwest. A storm system anchored over the Pacific Ocean
southwest of San Diego whipped up wind gusting to 35 mph across the
mountains of southern California.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at San Simeon, Calif., to 102 at Garden City, Kan. The low
Saturday morning was 38 at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Sunday, scattered afternoon showers and thunderstorms were
forecast from the upper Great Lakes into northern parts of the
middle Mississippi Valley, and across the western side of the
central Rockies. Scattered showers and thunderstorms also were
forecast from the southern Appalachians into the central Gulf Coast
and Florida.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the central and southern
California coast; between 100 and 105 across the central Plains
from south-central Nebraska into central and western Kansas, and in
the valleys of northern and central California; between 100 and 110
across the desert Southwest; and in the 80s or 90s across much of
the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
