<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovak-Arrests     06-18 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovak-Arrests,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Participants At Peace Seminar Deported, Report 12 Arrests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovak police detained at least 12
people and ordered 33 Westerners to leave the country after raiding
an unofficial peace seminar in Prague Saturday, an emigre
publication reported.
   The nationalities of the foreigners expelled were not given.
   More than 50 people had gathered in the Prague apartment of Jan
Urban despite warnings by police not to hold such meetings,
according to the London-based Palach Press.
   It said the police raid came after the participants signed a
statement condemning the disruptions by police of two peace
meetings Friday. The statement also supported a proposal by the
Czechoslovak human rights group Charter 77 to set up a ``European
Peace Parliament'' of non-governmental organizations.
   Police confiscated all of the documents and detained up to 12 of
the Czechoslovak participants, Palach Press said.
   It said 33 Westerners from at least 16 nations who were at the
meeting were ordered to leave Czechsolovakia immediately.
   Twenty people were detained Friday when police disrupted
meetings at two different apartments, the Palach Press said. All
were released after being told not to hold similar meetings,
according to the report.
   A third meeting dealing with conscientious objectors and
alternatives to military service was held Friday without police
intervention, Palach Press said.
</TEXT>
