<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Protest     06-18 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Protest,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Rough Up Pro-Reform Demonstrators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police beat and detained members of several
political groups who demonstrated Saturday in support of Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms, a witness reported.
   Yuri Mityunov, a member of the Democratic Union, a group that
proclaims itself an alternative to the Communist Party, said as
many as 10 people were attacked by police and taken away after the
hour-long rally by a few hundred demonstrators outside the office
of the government newspaper Izvestia.
   ``At the end of the demonstration, the police began to beat
demonstrators and some people were arrested,'' Mityunov said in a
telephone interview.
   He said he could not determine exactly how many were detained or
what happened to them.
   He said the demonstrators, members of four unofficial political
groups that support ``perestroika,'' or Gorbachev's program of
reforms in certain segments of society, were told by police their
demonstration was illegal because it was not registered with Moscow
city authorities.
   Demonstrators carried signs saying, ``Gorbachev we are with
you,'' Mityunov reported. He also said they protested special
privileges for top Communist Party officials and demanded a
political system based on the law.
   The demonstrators included members of the groups Perestroika 88,
Democratic Perestroika, Civil Dignity and Community, according to
Mityunov.
</TEXT>
