<HEAD>New York-Paris-Dakar Anti-Racism Concerts Held</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-racism concerts in three continents began
Saturday night with a message from President Francois Mitterrand
saying there was still work to be done in the fight for liberty,
equality and fraternity.
   The New York-Paris-Dakar concerts were organized by SOS-Racism,
France's largest anti-racist group.
   ``Music takes nourishment from all cultures ... all colors,''
Mitterrand said in a message to the Paris concert held on the
city's eastern outskirts at Vincennes. ``You are together tonight
because there is still work to be done in the fight for liberty,
equality and fraternity.''
   The Vincennes concert started at 7 p.m. (1 p.m. EDT) and was to
last till dawn.
   Concerts also were being held at the Demba Diop stadium in
Dakar, Senegal, and at the Apollo Theater in New York. Television
tapes showed excerpts at each concert of the other performances.
   Harlem Desir, president of SOS-Racism, flew to Dakar Friday in
the private jet of Senegalese President Abdou Diouf to be present
for the Dakar concert where Zaire's Kanda Bongo Man and Jamaica's
the Wailers were among the performers.
