<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia-Rebels     06-18 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Rebels,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eritrean rebels claim 810 government troopers killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eritrean rebels on Saturday claimed 810
government soldiers were killed in a three-day battle at a major
military outpost in Eritrea province in northern Ethiopia.
   They also said 1,240 soldiers were wounded in the fight for the
garrison headquarters near the town of Keren, 55 miles northeast of
the Eritrean administrative capital of Asmara.
   That would be near a main highway used to transport relief aid
to drought victims.
   The rebels' clandestine radio station Voice of the Broad Masses
of Eritrea said in a broadcast monitored in Nairobi the offensive
was mounted by guerrillas of the Eritrean People's Liberation Front
last Tuesday and ended Thursday when the soldiers abandoned their
positions. It did not give any casualties for the rebels who are
fighting for an independent Eritrea.
   Foreign aid workers distributing relief supplies to hundreds of
thousands of drought victims in Eritrea were recently evacuated
from the north on orders of the Marxist government. It said
supplies were going to the rebels.
   There was no indpendent confirmation of the rebels' claim.
Government officials in Addis Ababa, the Ethiopian capital, were
not available for comment.
   Foreign observers say both sides in the 27-year-old civil war
frequently exaggerate their claims of victories.
   The secessionist rebels said their troops also captured 388
weapons, six radio sets and a large amount of ammunition.
</TEXT>
