<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Dominican-Critics     06-18 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican-Critics,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leaders Criticize Appointment of New Defense Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders on
Saturday criticized the reinstatement in the army of Interior
Minister Elias Wessin y Wessin and his designation as defense
minister by President Joaquin Balaguer.
   Balaguer reinstated Gen. Wessin y Wessin, a man once accused of
plotting Balaguer's ouster, on Friday after firing Defense Minister
Lt. Gen. Antonio Imbert Barrera.
   Wessin y Wessin, 60, an unsuccessful candidate in the 1968 and
1982 presidential elections, was interior minister in 1971 when
Balaguer sent him into exile, accusing him of planning to overthrow
the government. He returned in 1978 and in 1986 backed Balaguer's
successful campaign and later was named interior minister.
   Jose Francisco Pena Gomez, head of the opposition Dominican
Revolutionary Party, called Wessin y Wessin's designation
``inconvenient, inopportune and a violation of the constitution of
the republic.''
   ``That post should be held by army officers who are first in
line in the military hierarchy, not by an active politician with a
controversial past in Dominican politics, especially at the level
of the armed forces,'' Pena Gomez said.
   The general secretary of the Dominican Communist Party, Narciso
Isa Conde, said the appointment of Wessin y Wessin was done to
please the United States. He said that after being outside of the
armed forces for more than 20 years Wessin y Wessin assumed his new
position ``without any kind of leadership'' in the military.
   Wessin y Wessin is the third defense minister designated by
Balaguer in the 23 months.
   Barrera, 66, is the only surviving member of the group of 12 men
who in 1961 ambused and assasinated dictator Rafael L. Trujillo.
Congress declared him a national hero and general-for-life in 1962
for bringing an end to 30 years of dictatorship.
   In a decree released late Friday Balaguer designated Barrera as
a general inspector at the service of the president and praised his
``high merits and notable services to his country, which have
contributed to strengthen the nation's institutions.''
   In 1963, Wessin y Wessin and other military officers
participated in the overthrow of leftist President Juan Bosch that
eventually led to the 1965 civil war. Wessin y Wessin led the fight
and asked the United States to intervene.
   After the war Wessin y Wessin was sent to Panama as a military
attache and he retired from the army in 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
