<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 1946EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FBI-CentralAmerica     06-18 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI-Central America,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Reportedly Made Four Probes Into Opponents of Central American
Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI conducted at least four investigations of
opponents of the Reagan Administration's Central American polices,
according to documents disclosed by a newspaper Saturday.
   The FBI investigated critics of Reagan administration policies
in Nicaragua in one probe and groups planning or staging
demonstrations against U.S. policy in Nicaragua in another, The
Boston Globe reported.
   The agency also conducted two investigations into opponents of
U.S. policies in El Salvador, the newspaper said. The probes were
captioned ``Salvadoran Leftist Activities in the United States''
and ``International Terrorism Investigation re: Leftist Guerrilla
Activities in El Salvador,'' the newspaper reported.
   The Globe said it obtained the documents under the Freedom of
Information Act.
   The FBI also conducted a separate investigation into members of
TecNica, a group that sends engineers to Nicaragua to work on small
scale development projects, the newspaper reported.
   Benjamin Linder, a 27-year-old American engineer who was killed
last year by contra forces, was working with a group affiliated
with TecNica.
   A House subcommittee last year looked into the possibility that
the FBI's interviews of TecNica volunteers returning from Nicaragua
amounted to an unwarranted investigation of the group.
   In addition to the investigations reported by The Globe, two
congressional committees and FBI Director William Sessions are
investigating the bureau's conduct in its probe of the Committee in
Solidarity with the People of El Salvador.
   The Globe asked the Center for Constitutional Rights, a public
interest lawyers group based in New York City, to analyze the
documents.
   David Lerner, a group lawyer, said the documents indicated that
the FBI's activity was even more widespread than previously
believed.
   ``The FBI's surveillance of opponents of all the Reagan's
Central America policies is pervasive. Anyone active in opposing
U.S. policy in all of Central America seems to have been a
target,'' the newspaper quoted Lerner as saying.
   But FBI spokeswoman Sue Schnitzer denied that the bureau's
investigations are politically motivated.
   ``We don't go after people because of politics. We go after
people we suspect of committing a violation of U.S. law,'' the
paper quoted Schnitzer as saying.
   Ann Mari Buitrago of the Center for Constitutional Rights was
quoted as saying it is impossible to determine the number or extent
of the various FBI investigations because most of the documents
have been blacked out.
   One of the two Nicaraguan documents is captioned ``Nicaraguan
Terrorist Matters: International Terrorism _ Nicaragua,'' the
newspaper reported. It contains a report on a 1986 demonstration in
Chicago by Pledge of Resistance, a group that began protesting the
administration's pro-contra policies around 1985.
   In 1985, after being questioned by Congress, former FBI Director
William Webster admitted that FBI agents interviewed more than 100
U.S. citizens who had visited Nicaragua, as well as their friends,
landlords and employees, in some cases.
   Webster said then that some of those interviews may have been
requested by the CIA or the National Security Council.
   The FBI has maintained that its interviews were prompted by
counterintelligence concerns, such as fears that travelers may have
been asked by Nicaraguan officials to obtain information or spy on
the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880618-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 1942EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Thatcher 2ndLd-Writethru a0621 06-18 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Thatcher, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0621,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 15 grafs to update with Thatcher quotes, legal honor
ceremony. Picks up 11th graf pvs, ``Mrs. Thatcher is xxx'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said
Saturday she'll do some ``vigorous batting'' at the seven-nation
economic summit, and aides said it will include pushing for ``farm
subsidy disarmament'' and debt relief for the poorest African
countries.
   At a ceremony in the paneled library of Toronto's Osgoode Hall
within hours of her arrival, Mrs. Thatcher was made an honorary
``bencher,'' or senior lawyer, of the Law Society of Upper Canada.
   Addressing the black-gowned members of the society, the
profession's governing body in the province of Ontario, Mrs.
Thatcher noted that the summit opening Sunday coincided with an
cricket match between Canadian graduates of Britain's ancient
Oxford and Cambridge universities.
   ``It won't be the only match in town,'' said Mrs. Thatcher. ``I
intend to do some fairly vigorous batting myself on a different
pitch.''
   Earlier, the British spokesman, who insisted on anonymity, said
Mrs. Thatcher hoped the three-day summit would provide impetus for
farm subsidy reform at the December mid-term review in Montreal of
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, which regulates
international trade.
   Britain is seeking ``farm subsidy disarmament rather than farm
subsidy armament,'' said the Thatcher spokesman.
   ``I don't think we would regard the elimination of all subsidies
by the year 2000 as a practical solution but we ought to be moving
in that direction,'' said the spokesman.
   The United States wants all farm subsidies eliminated by that
date. But West European countries and Japan envisage only reducing
the subsidies.
   The spokesman said Mrs. Thatcher, as well as Chancellor of the
Exchequer Nigel Lawson, would also be pushing for joint action on
relieving the debt burden of the poorest African countries.
   ``There should be a fairly specific agreement on African debt in
particular. We're looking for a firm commitment for action,'' he
said.
   Earlier, some Ontario lawyers protested granting Mrs. Thatcher
the ``bencher'' award, citing her refusal to impose tough sanctions
on South Africa.
   Clayton Ruby, one of the ``benchers'' who protested, said,
``This is a leader whose principal accomplishment has been to
frustrate Canada's attempts to end apartheid.''
   Laura Legge, acting head of the 191-year-old society, said only
three of the 44 ``benchers'' had protested, adding: ``Margaret
Thatcher, regardless of one's politics, is a woman who has been
highly successful.''
   In a her acceptance speech, Mrs. Thatcher said the right to live
under the rule of law will be the test of the Soviet Union's policy
of glasnost or openness.
   ``That will be the key test of whether the changes we are seeing
in the Communist societies are a true step toward democracy,'' she
said.
   Mrs. Thatcher is the 13th honorary ``bencher'' in the society's
history. They include Elizabeth, mother of Britain's Queen
Elizabeth II, and former Canadian Governor General Roland Michener.
   Britain is a major South African trading partner. Mrs. Thatcher
has refused to impose embargoes, saying they would hurt the black
majority most, encourage white resistance to change and cost jobs
in Britain and South Africa.
   Canada, which had scant economic ties with South Africa, has
been a leading proponent of tough measures by the Commonwealth, the
48-nation association of Britain and its former colonies.
   Earlier, Canadian officials and fur trappers lauded a British
decision not to insist fur coats carry warnings that the animals
may have been cruelly trapped.
   The government proposal, drawn up under pressure from
animal-rights activists, would have made retailers and
manufacturers put the labels in wild fox and lynx coats, but not in
minks.
   ``It is an especially Canadian victory _ kids, teachers,
parliamentarians got behind the trappers and native people and
brought political pressure to the highest level in Britain,'' said
Canadian Fur Institute spokesman Kirk Smith in an interview with
Toronto's Globe and Mail.
   The fur industry employs 100,000 Canadians, about half of them
native Indians and Inuit, and is worth more than $400 million a
year.
   Mrs. Thatcher appeared likely to discuss with Canadian Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney a lucrative $10 billion contract to sell
Canada 10-12 nuclear-powered submarines, which France is also
trying to win. Mulroney is also hosting French President Francois
Mitterrand at the summit.
   Britain is seeking to sell the Canadians its Trafalgar-class
submarine, built with U.S. technology.
   Under an Anglo-American agreement, Britain must get U.S.
permission to pass on the technology to a third country. President
Reagan said last month he would not object, but Congress still must
give its approval.
   France would sell Canada its smaller, and cheaper, Rubis
Amethyste submarine, built entirely with French technology.
</TEXT>
