<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Houghton, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0604,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commander Of Navy Medical Lab Killed In Car Wreck</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to add details on his work, death and
survivors.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capt. James O. Houghton, commanding
officer of the Naval Aerospace Medical Research Laboratory, has
died as a result of an automobile accident, police said. He was 45.
   Houghton was killed Thursday night when his car collided head-on
with a speeding car that veered into his lane, said Florida Highway
Patrol officer Venus North.
   Houghton did important research into the human body's reaction
to gravitational forces tolerance in high performance aircraft in
the early 1980s, according to Lt. Cmdr. Tom Fleischman.
   Houghton had commanded the laboratory at Pensacola Naval Air
Station since June 1985, and beginning July 1 was to take a new job
overseeing medical research and development at the Naval Medical
Command in Washington, D.C.
   Born in Littlefield, Texas, Houghton graduated from Union
College in Nebraska and earned his medical degree at Loma Linda
University in California. He interned at the Philadelphia Naval
Hospital in 1969 and was designated a naval flight surgeon the
following year.
   He served with the First and Third Marine Air Wings in Santa
Ana, Calif.; Da Nang, Vietnam; and Futenma, Okinawa, and had been
senior medical officer aboard the USS Oriskany and the USS Midway.
   Houghton conducted research in acceleration physiology at the
Naval Air Development Center in Warminister, Pa. He also worked as
a special assistant for aerospace medicine at the Naval Air Systems
Command in Washington, D.C.
   Funeral arrangements for Houghton, who was single, were not
immediately released by the Navy. He is survived by three brothers
and three sisters.
</TEXT>
