<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gun-Graduation 1stLd-Writethru a0565 06-18 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gun-Graduation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0565,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fresno Graduate Gets Pistol For College</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds two grafs on license requirement, gun being registered</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When 18-year-old Joely Kragh leaves home
for college this fall, she'll pack what she calls an unexpected but
reassuring high school graduation present: a .38-caliber pistol.
   ``I was shocked at first. I hadn't expected it,'' Ms. Kragh said
Friday of the gift from her parents.
   She likes the idea of having a handgun in her sports car while
she drives 250 miles alone on the freeways between Fresno and the
University of California at Irvine, where she plans to study
biological sciences.
   ``It's more reassuring to know it's there. It's like having a
security blanket,'' she added.
   Her mother, Geri Kragh, said she first thought of buying a
handgun for her oldest daughter after seeing a television talk show
program on date-rape, murders and violence on college campuses. The
stories were similar to what Mrs. Kragh, who attends Fresno State
University, reads in the campus newspaper.
   ``I just want her to have the option to have the protection if
she wants it,'' Mrs. Kragh said.
   Her daughter plans to attend self-defense classes in college.
But at 5-feet-2-inches tall and weighing about 90 pounds, she's
doubtful she could wrestle off a large attacker.
   ``I originally kind of approached it as a joke and in fact
didn't tell my husband until the night we bought it,'' Mrs. Kragh
recalled. Larry Kragh, a former reserve sheriff's deputy, mulled
over the idea as the couple sat in the car outside a sports store.
   ``The more he thought about it, the more he thought it would be
a good idea,'' Mrs. Kragh said.
   ``I didn't think my dad would go for it,'' Ms. Kragh said as she
prepared for a post-graduation vacation cruise in the Carribean.
She graduated from Hoover High School on Tuesday.
   She has completed a gun safety class, where she said she was by
far the youngest person at the firing range.
   The gun is registered, and she plans to carry it unloaded and in
a container to avoid the need for the license required for carrying
concealed weapons, Mrs. Kragh said.
   Obtaining such a license is extremely difficult, and applicants
have to state a reason, said Fresno Police Lt. Lynn Button. ``It
has to be a good and sound reason for personal safety,'' Button
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
