<HEAD>Mozambican Rebels Claim Government, Zimbabwe Forces Fired On
Civilians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mozambique's anti-Marxist rebels on
Saturday claimed that government and Zimbabwean troops fired on
civilians waiting for Red Cross aid, killing 17 people and wounding
65.
   According to a statement issued in Lisbon by the Mozambican
National Resistance, the attack took place Tuesday in the town of
Molima 17 miles from the city of Chemba. It said the attack was
witnessed by eight Red Cross staff members.
   The statement signed by the rebels' Lisbon spokesman Manuel
Frank also said that on June 8 there was a similar attack on
civilians who were waiting at a rural Red Cross outpost for medical
and food supplies. It gave no further details.
   Zimbabwe has troops in Mozambique helping the government battle
the guerrillas.
   Both Zimbabwe and Mozambique claim South Africa is helping the
rebels. South Africa has denied the allegations.
