<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MississippiPicnic 1stLd-Writethru a0624 06-18 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mississippi Picnic, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0624,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Wakes Up And Smells The Catfish</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6th graf ``Most people'' to CORRECT guitarist's name to
``Booby'' sted Bobby</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer_</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the sounds of Delta Blues in the air, more
than 1,000 transplanted Mississippians gathered for a down-home
fish fry and picnic in Central Park Saturday.
   Four propane cookers fried up 150 pounds of catfish fillets and
thousands of hush puppies for the Ninth Annual Way Up North in
Mississippi Picnic.
   ``It's a slice of what's very common in Mississippi every
weekend _ people having outdoor parties,'' said Tim James, who
moved to New York 10 years ago from Columbus, Miss. ``If the
buildings weren't here, it could be somebody's farm.''
   ``Primarily it's a fun thing,'' said Mississippi Lt. Gov. Brad
Dye, as he ate catfish and bragged about its freshness.
   Mississippi exported about 2 million pounds of pond-raised,
grain-fed catfish last year. And catfish farming in the Delta is
the fastest growing industry in the state, said Jeff Giachelli,
director of marketing for the state Department of Agriculture.
   Most people came for the camaraderie and brought their own box
lunches to spread out on blankets under the trees as they listened
to Roosevelt ``Booby'' Barnes play his slide guitar.
   But Eleanor Roberts of Manhattan, who has no connection wih
Mississippi, said unabashedly that she came for the free catfish,
courtesy of Country Skillet Catfish Company of Isola, and hush
puppies, donated by the Mississippi Hush Puppy Company.
   ``It's like a cross between a perch and a butterfish, very
sweet,'' said Ms. Roberts who fretted that there might not be any
left by the time she got to the head of the long line.
   In addition to the food, there were the universities, all trying
to outdo each other in giving away the best souvenirs _ football
schedules, embossed pencils, bumper stickers, fans and lapel pins.
   The University of Mississippi table was set up next to
Mississippi State's.
   ``Up here we sort of mix together and put aside the feelings of
combat,'' said Charles Weatherly of Ripley, Miss., a former
president of the MSU alumni association. ``We are coming together
to promote the state.''
   At the Mississippi University for Women's table, alumnae spoke
about the admission of men early this decade after a man went all
the way to the Supreme Court to get into ``the W's'' nursing school.
   How many men now attend the W?
   ``Too many,'' replied Kay Cobb, former president of the alumnae
association.
   There were not many black people at the picnic, but those who
attended had good things to say about the state.
   ``If the state was like it is now when I finished college
(Alcorn State 1935) I'd have stayed there,'' said Walter Harbour of
Queens, who was born in Indianola, Miss., 78 years ago.
   Lionel Hampton, the jazz musician, who called himself an adopted
Mississippian, said he was the first black on the campus of Ole
Miss back in 1950, although he was performing, not studying.
   ``I never got such ovation, before or since,'' Hampton said.
   In a brief ceremony, the Mississippi Society of New York, which
organized the picnic, and the Mississippi Printing Co. of
Greenwood, which helped pay for it, presented a $5,000 check to New
York's Parks Commissioner Henry Stern.
   Stern noted that the Mississippi picnic was such a good idea
that it is being copied by Louisiana, which has scheduled a picnic
in the park July 16.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
