<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soccer-Violence 2dLd-Writethru   06-18 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soccer-Violence, 2d Ld-Writethru,a0588,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>English Fans Ransack Bar; About 300 People Arrested In Soccer
Violence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with British fans ransacking
bar, more arrests. Pickup 11th graf pvs ``The violence....'' SUBS
15th graf pvs ```They (the English)...''' with one graf to CONFORM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   English rowdies rampaged through
a bar late Saturday and police arrested about two dozen more German
and British soccer fans in Frankfurt in a third straight night of
disturbances.
   Police reported about 300 English and German hoodlums, including
16 right-wing extremists, were arrested or placed under preventive
detention in three cities in the latest round of clashes and
vandalism by soccer fans.
   Police rounded up about two dozen English and German soccer fans
Saturday night several hours after the Soviet Union's 3-1 soccer
victory over England.
   Following the match, hundreds of police patrolled Frankfurt's
main train station where disturbances had broken out late Friday.
   Some English rowdies were arrested after they ransacked a bar
where they had been drinking, according to police.
   They said groups of Germans were picked up for public
drunkenness and because it appeared they were preparing to attack
English soccer fans.
   Frankfurt police Saturday afternoon said that in addition to 88
arrests late Friday and early Saturday, 12 other brawling fans had
been arrested just before the game between England and the Soviets.
   ``I don't know if they were English or German. We had a mix of
both before,'' police spokesman Manfred Fuellhardt said in a
telephone interview.
   In Gelsenkirchen, 50 known West German troublemakers were taken
into temporary custody as a preventive measure before the start of
the Netherlands-Ireland soccer match, according to officials.
   The Dutch won the game 1-0 and no incidents were reported.
   Frankfurt police spokesman Kurt Kraus said 16 right-wing
extremists arrested in Frankfurt early Saturday ``are members of
the notorious Eagle Front fan club.'' The Eagle Front is a group of
young fans who often have tatoos of neo-Nazi emblems.
   Dozens of those arrested were English fans on their
self-proclaimed ``Invasion of Germany 1988.'' Many of the fans were
infuriated that their team already had been eliminated from the
championships even before the match with the Soviets.
   The violence surrounding the European soccer championships
already has led to more than 700 arrests in five German cities and
forced cancellation of the English clubs' bid to rejoin European
tournament play next season.
   In the Bavarian capital of Munich, police arrested 120 fans, all
West German except for one English fan, for brawls that broke out
as the host team beat Spain 2-0 Friday in Olympic Stadium.
   Late Friday night, groups of English, West German and Italian
rowdies got into isolated scuffles near the train station, police
said.
   Police charged at and dispersed dozens of the drunken fans,
officials said.
   ``They (the English) came out of a bar looking for trouble and
they got it,'' said Peter Staskiewecz, another police spokesman.
   The English were arrested for throwing beer bottles, brawling
with tavern patrons and attacking two motorists at red lights near
the train station, Frankfurt police said. The drivers were slightly
injured and their cars damaged, police said.
   The brawls have forced many Frankfurt residents to stay away
from areas near the main train station and the Sachsenhausen
district.
   ``English Fans Fight their Way through Sachsenhausen,'' said the
front-page headline in Saturday's editions of the Frankfurter Neue
Presse daily.
   Police on Friday said the body of a 29-year-old Irish soccer fan
was found floating in the Main River running through Frankfurt.
   Police said the victim apparently drowned while intoxicated and
that there was no indication of foul play. The body was discovered
Thursday night.
   The soccer-related clashes broke out shortly after the two-week
European championships started on June 10. Most of those arrested
have been released after spending the night in jail.
   The violence by English fans already has prompted England to
withdraw its application for readmission to European club soccer
tournaments next season.
   English clubs were banned after the 1985 Heysel stadium tragedy
in Belgium in which 39 people, most of them Italians, were killed
in violence sparked by rampaging English soccer fans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
