<DOCNO> AP880618-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 2043EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0605 06-18 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0605,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Sounds Confident Note In Southern Campaign Swing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS final graf pvs with 5 grafs on meeting with Wallace</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, expressing growing confidence
about his chances to win the presidency, told Texas Democrats
Saturday to ignore predictions he can't carry the South. ``Vamos a
ganar,'' he told them. ``We're going to win.''
   Dukakis brought Texas Democratic Convention delegates to their
feet Saturday, cheering, first in Spanish, then in English, ``We're
going to win.''
   In a speech to the convention, Dukakis said, ``If anyone tells
that we can't win in the South, or that we can't win in the West,
or that we can't win in the great state of Texas, don't you believe
it.
   ``You tell them that we're going to win.''
   Texas is the adopted home state of Republican George Bush, but
Dukakis refuses to concede the state to the vice president.
   One order of business at the state convention was to complete
allocation of delegates to the Democratic National Convention.
   Dukakis edged Jesse Jackson in the Texas primary on March 8, but
in a separate system of caucuses in Texas, Jackson gained ground.
According to The Associated Press delegate count, Dukakis could
expect support from 76 Texas delegates, while 71 would back
Jackson. Another 64 were uncommitted, including delegates
previously pledged to Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
   However, those figures could shift as the delegate selection
moves through its final stages.
   Gore planned to ask his delegates to switch to Dukakis on Monday.
   One of Dukakis' strengths in Texas is his support in the
Hispanic community, stemming in part from his fluent Spanish.
   Before he flew to the Democratic convention he was in San
Antonio where he delivered a eulogy at the funeral of William
Velasquez, founder of the Southwest Voter Registration and
Education Project, an organization credited with getting hundreds
of thousands of Hispanics registered to vote.
   Velasquez, who died of cancer on Wednesday, had planned to
introduce Dukakis to the state convention.
   ``He was our friend,'' Dukakis told mourners who packed St.
Mary's Roman Catholic Church. ``We learned from him, we were
inspired by him, we will never forget him.''
   Shifting to Spanish, Dukakis said, ``Willie was a nuts-and-bolts
political leader, but his commitment went deeper than that _ to the
very soul of this country, to the very heart of our democratic
system. ... His goal was not to change the faces of those we elect
to public service, but to improve the quality of public service
itself.''
   In his speech to the Houston convention, Dukakis recalled the
1960 presidential election when Massachusetts Sen. John F. Kennedy
picked Texan Lyndon B. Johnson as his running mate.
   ``Today, as in 1960, we're in a battle for the economic future
of America and now, as then, the old ways simply will not do.''
   He ridiculed Bush's criticism of his Harvard ties, saying,
``Some people say this election is about where we went to college.
I say it's about whether our children will have the chance to go to
college.''
   Dukakis said the Democrats were the party of working Americans,
of families, of progress, of strength and of the future.
   ``We're going to win because we're America's party,'' he said.
   From Texas, Dukakis flew to Montgomery, Ala., for a meeting with
former Gov. George C. Wallace.
   After a brief session at Wallace's suburban Montgomery home, the
two men spoke with reporters in front of the house.
   ``I appreciate him coming to Alabama,'' said the former
governor, who is hard of hearing and uses a wheelchair.
   Dukakis shook hands with Wallace and promised, ``I'll be back,
I'll be back.''
   The Massachusetts governor then attended a rally at a hotel in
downtown Montgomery.
</TEXT>
