<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 2145EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Economy     06-18 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Economy,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Says Economic Reforms Necessary to Defend Revolution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writera</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega on Saturday
defended economic reforms enacted by his government last week and
said the measures were necessary to strengthen the leftist
revolution.
   Facing a sometimes hostile audience of 1,000 people in an open
meeting, Ortega insisted his reforms were based in ``an economy of
a socialist nature.''
   The government on Wednesday devalued the cordoba, Nicaragua's
currency, nearly doubled gasoline prices and enacted a general pay
raise of 30 percent.
   Ortega last week said the government would lift wage and price
controls in hopes of stimulating productivity.
   Two unions controlled by the opposition Socialist Party on
Friday demanded 600 percent wage hikes to keep up with inflation
and the primary school teachers guild said it also will pursue a
salary increase.
   Explaining the measures to the crowd, Ortega said ``the greatest
problem is provoked by Yankee aggression.''
   The United States has maintained a three-year-old economic
embargo against Nicaragua and supported a more than six-year rebel
insurgency against the leftist Sandinista regime. The Reagan
administration recently has been discussing new military aid to the
rebels, known as Contras.
   The Nicaraguan government estimates the civil war has caused $3
billion in damage to the economy.
   Several people attending the meeting, one in a series the
government terms ``Face the People,'' complained the 30 percent
general pay raise failed to make up for rising food costs prompted
by the reforms.
   ``The problem here is hunger and nothing else,'' a health worker
told the president.
   Ortega called on his audience to mount ``a great
political-ideological effort'' to ensure the success of the
measures.
   ``We are convinced that we are going to surmount this historical
moment and will have better conditions to attend to all of the
demands of Nicaraguan workers,'' Ortega said.
</TEXT>
