<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Genscher     06-18 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Genscher,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Genscher: NATO Should Also Be Ready to Make Compromises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher said Saturday that NATO and the Warsaw Pact should both
strive toward eliminating their capacities to launch surprise
attacks on each other.
   Speaking in an interview on the West German radio station
Deutsche Welle, Genscher said the Warsaw Pact must be prepared to
``undertake asymmetrical disarmament steps'' because of its
advantage over NATO in tanks and other conventional forces.
   ``Conventional imbalances make up the central problem for
European security,'' Genscher said.
   But he suggested NATO itself should also be prepared to make
sacrifices.
   ``It is crucial that we now concentrate on creating conventional
forces stability and ... on eliminating both sides' capabilities
for surprise attacks,'' Genscher said.
   Genscher's remarks came a week after he praised a new Soviet
proposal for a three-stage plan to reduce NATO's and the Warsaw
Pact's conventional forces. Some U.S. officials see the proposal as
Soviet propaganda move.
</TEXT>
