<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Thailand-Toxic     06-18 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thailand-Toxic,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Toxic Waste Dumped at Bangkok Port</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reported Saturday that the
capital's river port has been used for years as an international
garbage dump for toxic waste.
   The English-language daily ``The Nation'' said thousands of
unclaimed, falsely-marked containers of toxic waste believed to
have been shipped from Singapore were being kept at Kloeng Toey
port.
   Tests done by the National Environment Board revealed the tanks
contained toxic chemical waste that could not be buried for fear it
would contaminate groundwater and not decompose for 20 or 30 years,
the Bangkok-based newspaper said.
   Port officials, the Industry Ministry and the National
Environment Board were searching for ways to dispose of the
unclaimed barrels, the newspaper said.
   Thai government officials could not immediately be reached for
comment Saturday.
   The Nation said fears were aroused after toxic waste began
leaking out of 360 tanks that were delivered at the port about four
years ago. Port authorities then alerted the National Enviroment
Board.
   The newspaper quoted port authorities as saying that in the
past, toxic waste was sent back to Singapore if the exporter's name
and the Thai receiver's address were known.
   Metal and plastic tanks labeled as liquid fertilizer or chemical
substances had been arriving regularly at Klong Toey port from
Singapore since 1978, the newspaper said.
   All cargo unloaded at the dock is supposed to be picked up
withing 75 days. If no one claims it the port can confiscate and
auction it off. Thai law restricts the opening of arriving cargo by
port officials.
   The Nation quoted Singapore's Counsellor Toh Hock Ghim as saying
his embassy had never been informed of the problem and that no Thai
authorities had ever asked help in tracking down the consigners of
the shipments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
