<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0602 06-18 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0602,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Prays For Rain</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS 2 grafs with Jackson's later appearances in Pennsylvania</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS CONRAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson stood in a Republican's
cornfield and prayed for rain Saturday.
   ``We call upon you because we know that you have the power to
bring forth sunshine and bring forth the rain,'' Jackson prayed in
a drought-stricken cornfield on Dan Mau's 1,400-acre farm in nearby
Chatham.
   Mau, a registered Republican, said he had not decided whom he
would support for president but added that Jackson, a Democrat,
made a good impression.
   ``I think he ought to have some influence on what happens in the
next few years,'' he said.
   Later, Jackson related his farm visit to the audience of more
than 1,000 people at the Illinois Democratic convention at Sangamon
State University and declared there should be a national moratorium
on farm foreclosures.
   ``No one should lose his land because of this drought,'' Jackson
said before leading a group prayer for rain and peace.
   Although Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis has garnered more
than enough delegates to be the party's nominee, Jackson urged
those gathered Saturday to endorse his presidential candidacy
instead.
   ``There is somebody running from Massachusetts with platitudes,
and there is somebody from Illinois running with ideas,'' said
Jackson, who has a home in Chicago and founded the Chicago-based
civil rights group, Operation PUSH.
   ``I stood with you to make a better and stronger Illinois ...
you didn't meet me through some commercial,'' said Jackson, who
disclosed that he is inviting Polish Solidarity Union founder Lech
Walesa and South African anti-apartheid activist Winnie Mandela to
the Democratic National Convention.
   State Treasurer Jerry Cosentino announced immediately afterward
that he would vote for Jackson on the first ballot at the national
convention in Atlanta next month.
   Cosentino had been a delegate for Sen. Paul Simon, but was
released along with other Simon delegates to vote as he wishes in
Atlanta after the senator from Illinois dropped out.
   ``As long as he decided to get out of the race, I'm not going to
turn my back on another man from Illinois,'' Cosentino said.
   Cosentino said Jackson deserves to be supported for president or
vice president.
   Jackson, in a news conference with reporters at the convention,
refused to say whether he wants to be named as Dukakis' running
mate.
   ``My constituents _ nearly seven million voters _ has earned
consideration,'' he said.
   Chicago Mayor Eugene Sawyer introduced Jackson as one of the
nation's strongest Democrats.
   ``He earned the right to be whatever he wants to be _ president,
vice president, whatever,'' Sawyer said.
   State Democrats were meeting in Springfield to adopt a platform,
name three candidates for University of Illinois trustee positions,
and nominate electors for the Electoral College.
   Later, Jackson attended a gathering in a park in Philadelphia to
celebrate black heritage.
   ``We're going to the White House,'' he told the group. ``Michael
Dukakis has never lived in public housing, so he probably couldn't
adjust...I want to go back to living in public housing. I want to
live in the White House.''
</TEXT>
