<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Lehman-Probe     06-18 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehman-Probe,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports: Lehman May Have Warned Target Of Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Navy Secretary John F. Lehman Jr. may
have tipped off a friend that he was a target in the federal
investigation of alleged widespread fraud and corruption in Defense
Department procurement, according to published reports.
   The Los Angeles Times and the Washington Post reported in their
Sunday editions that federal investigations are pursuing
information that Lehman may have warned Melvyn R. Paisley, former
assistant Navy secretary who later became a successful defense
consultant, that his telephones were being tapped in a massive
probe of defense contracting fraud.
   The Post quoted law enforcement sources as saying that questions
about Lehman focus on whether he may have obstructed justice by
warning Paisley that his activities might be the subject of a
federal investigation.
   The Times, however, quoted sources as saying the information is
``nothing close'' to strong enough at this point for considering
charges against Lehman.
   The Times cited an unidentified source as saying the alleged
warning, signs of which came to agents through a wiretap, took
place before Lehman left office in April, 1987. But the Post quoted
one source as saying the alleged warning occurred after both men
had left government service.
   Henry E. Hudson, U.S. attorney in Alexandria, Va., who is
coordinating the investigation, responded with a terse ``no
comment'' when asked by Sen. Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa, whether
Lehman was a target of the fast-developing federal inquiry by the
FBI, believed to be the largest in the nation's defense contracting
history.
   The Times said Lehman, at his McLean, Va., home, refused
Saturday to answer questions about the probe, saying: ``It would be
inappropriate of me to comment on an ongoing investigation.'' He
said he would break his silence ``after the investigation is
completed.''
   Lehman and Paisley have been close associates for years. As an
official of the Boeing Co., Paisley hired Lehman as a consultant
nearly a decade ago. Lehman then recruited Paisley to become
assistant Navy secretary in 1981, and he served as Navy research
chief until 1987.
   Law enforcement sources have identified Paisley as a central
figure in the probe of Pentagon contracting. His home and office
were searched Tuesday. Sources familiar with the investigation have
said authorities bugged his consulting office and tapped his
telephone.
   The nationwide federal investigation, which involves private
defense consultants, Pentagon officials and defense contractors,
was made public last Tuesday as agents searched 38 offices and
homes in an effort to find evidence of bribes and gratuities paid
for disclosure of confidential contracting information. The
information allegedly gave recipients a competitive edge in
submitting bids for contracts.
</TEXT>
