<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 2233EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavyDeath     06-18 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Where Recruit Drowned To Reopen Next Week With New Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>APPLETON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Navy Rescue Swimmer School at
Pensacola, Fla., which was closed after a recruit drowned in March,
will reopen Monday with new instructors and safety guidelines, a
congressional aide said Saturday.
   John Fink, an aide to Rep. Toby Roth, R-Wis., said the Navy
would announce the reopening Monday.
   Navy officials in Pensacola did not return telephone calls
Saturday.
   The Navy closed the school March 29 after an investigation into
the March 2 drowning of Lee Mirecki, of Appleton, showed Mirecki
had been held underwater in the school's training pool.
   A medical examiner testified at a hearing earlier this month
that Mirecki, 19, died from heart failure caused by the ``sheer
terror'' of being held underwater against his will.
   Five instructors face possible court-martial on charges of
involuntary manslaughter in Mirecki's death, and the officer in
charge of the school faces court-martial for dereliction of duty.
   Fink said one of the school's new guidelines will prohibit
instructors from physically handling students in the water.
Instead, students will practice rescue techniques and combat skills
on each other while instructors supervise, he said.
   Fink said the reopening announcement originally was scheduled
for Friday but was delayed because of a question about the wording
of one new guideline.
   The announcement planned for Friday stated that ``unauthorized
exercises such as `sharks and daisies' will be prohibited,'' Fink
said. He said he asked Lt. Cmdr. Michael McGuire, a congressional
liaison officer, about the phrasing because it was the Navy's first
known reference to an exercise being unauthorized.
   After consulting his superiors, McGuire said the announcement
would be withheld until Monday, Fink said.
   According to testimony at the hearing, Mirecki died during a
``sharks and daisies'' exercise in which students swim face down
while instructors roam the side of the pool, periodically jumping
on students to simulate attacks by potential drowning victims.
Rescue students are expected to free themselves from the attacker.
   The new guidelines also will address how to handle requests to
drop a class, Fink said.
   Testimony at the hearing revealed that Mirecki screamed the
letters DOR, which stand for ``drop on request,'' but instructors
forced him back into the pool to continue the exercise.
   Under the school's rules, he should have been permitted to drop
the class, officials said.
   Meanwhile, The Appleton-Post Crescent reported Saturday that two
sources, who requested anonymity, said a recommendation on whether
to court-martial the six men charged in Mirecki's death has been
delivered to Rear Adm. David Morris. He has 120 days to dismiss the
charges, discipline the six or order military trials.
   The newspaper said a decision is expected in July.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
