<1ST_LINE>r a AM-USAir     06-18 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USAir,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Sues Flight Attendants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir has filed suit against its 4,000 flight
attendants and their union, claiming their refusal to work overtime
during the Memorial Day weekend cost the airline $1.1 million in
canceled flights and other costs.
   ``The reason we filed was so this illegal job action would not
be repeated,'' USAir spokesman David Shipley said Friday. ``We have
the Fourth of July holiday coming up.''
   USAir claims the job action violated the federal Railway Labor
Act. Officials of the Association of Flight Attendants said they
did nothing wrong and said the union's contract with USAir
maintains flight attendants do not have to work more than 85 hours
a month.
   The suit, filed recently in U.S. District Court in Pittsburgh,
asks the court to prohibit the employees from repeating the recent
action. It also seeks $1.1 million in damages.
   The airline said it was forced to cancel 179 flights,
inconveniencing about 10,000 passengers. It said it lost about $1
million in revenue and paid $100,000 to accommodate passengers
affected by the cancellations and to pay flight crews who already
had been scheduled for work.
</TEXT>
