<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 2234EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AccusedHijacker     06-18 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Accused Hijacker,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Released From Cuban Prison Awaits Trial in Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who spent five years in a
Cuban prison after being convicted of air piracy was released and
flown to Florida, where he now awaits trial for the same crime.
   Fidel Castro's government had sentenced Robert Patrick Richter
to 20 years in prison. The early release was credited to the
efforts of Richter's father, prominent Chicago-area businessman
John Richter, who also arranged for a twin-engine private plane to
fly his son from Cuba to Miami.
   Robert Richter, 31, was arrested Wednesday by the FBI as he
stepped off the plane. A federal magistrate in Fort Lauderdale
released him on bond Friday.
   Richter's father and the FBI declined to discuss how the deal
was struck with Cuban authorities. But the FBI said the U.S.
government was not involved in the negotiations.
   ``This is not an everyday common occurence,'' said FBI agent
Gene Frey. ``I'm happy that he's back.''
   Richter allegedly boarded an Air Florida jetliner at Fort
Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport on July 7, 1983, and
used a phony bomb to force the plane's crew to take him to Cuba,
the FBI said.
   Richter, who often had spoken of his interest in communism and
Cuba, arrived there at an inopportune time. Less than 24 hours
earlier, the U.S. government said it received word from Castro's
government that Cuba would crack down on hijackers and that any sky
pirates landing on the island could expect 50 years in prison.
   Looking gaunt and pale when he appeared before U.S. Magistrate
Lurana Snow, Richter pleaded innocent to a charge of air piracy
contained in a 1987 indictment. He was accompanied by his father,
who posted a $250,000 personal surety bond and promised that his
son would work in one of his businesses while awaiting trial.
   After his release, Richter refused to talk about conditions in
Cuban prison and would say only that he was ``very happy to be
back'' in the United States.
   ``The hijacking was a great mistake, a bad error in judgment
that we will explain to the court at a later date,'' said Richter's
attorney, Edward Swan. Swan said he would ask for a psychiatric
evaluation of Richter.
</TEXT>
