<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BigSteal     06-18 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Big Steal,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House That Was a Steal May Turn Big Profit, Authorities Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOODSIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A salesman accused of faking documents
to buy an $855,000 home in this exclusive community without making
a down payment or any monthly payments stands to make $500,000 from
its sale, authorities say.
   John Williams, 30, faces felony counts of using bogus tax
returns, income statements and identification to acquire a mortgage
to buy the home, but a prosecutor says Williams is the legal owner.
   ``If it is in his name, I personally don't see any reason why he
can't sell it,'' District Attorney Paul Wendler said.
   Williams, who makes $800 a month, has yet to make one of the
$6,500 monthly payments on the four-bedroom house on five acres
with swimming pool, spa, marble floors and a grand view of the
southern San Francisco Bay. The house recently was reappraised at
$1.3 million.
   The mortgage holder, World Savings and Loan Association, is
foreclosing, but if the sale for $1.2 million goes through before
foreclosure Williams could pocket a cool half-million-dollar profit.
   Williams' alleged scam was discovered in April when he reported
the theft of $5,400 worth of electronics equipment from the house.
San Mateo County Sheriff's Department investigators say he came in
the next day reporting that another $90,000 worth of items had also
been stolen, including $80,000 in clothing.
   ``That's when I got suspicious,'' said detective Bill Cody, who
then discovered Williams had phony income tax returns and W-2 forms
identifying him as a consultant with a yearly income of up to
$550,000.
</TEXT>
