<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 2255EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Earhart-Anniversary     06-18 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earhart-Anniversary,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Join Celebration On 60th Anniversary Of Earhart's Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATCHISON, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 350 people gathered outside Amelia
Earhart's hometown Saturday to commemorate the 60th anniversary of
the flight that made her the first woman to fly across the Atlantic.
   The 99s, an honorary society of female pilots founded by
Earhart, sponsored the celebration at the International Forest of
Friendship's Memory Lane.
   Earhart's sister, Muriel Earhart Morrissey, 87, of Boston,
attended the ceremonies, as did Russ Brinkley, of Harrisburg, Pa.,
a journalist who wrote the first story on Earhart before her
trans-Atlantic flight June 18, 1928.
   Earhart, who was 29 when she made her famous flight, departed
from Boston with two male co-pilots and landed in Carthmenshire,
South Wales, making the trip in 22 hours.
   She disappeared while attempting to fly around the world with
her navigator, Fred Noonan, on July 2, 1937, in the Pacific. No
trace of the pair or Earhart's plane was found, and she is
officially considered lost at sea.
   The 992 on Saturday also honored 45 people who have contributed
to aviation development, including actor James Stewart, retail
magnate Sam Walton, automaker Henry Ford, Adm. Wesley McDonald and
women aviators Opal McClung, Sophia Payton and Jo Eddleman.
</TEXT>
