<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 2309EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-O'HareInvestigation     06-18 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-O'Hare Investigation,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Reportedly Won't Consider Limit On Flights Per Hour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has refused
to consider reducing the number of flights at O'Hare International
Airport despite repeated requests by federal safety officials who
fear traffic overloads, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   The clash of positions was underscored in a May 31 letter from
the chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board to the
head of the FAA, the Chicago Tribune reported.
   The newspaper said NTSB Chairman Jim Burnett told FAA chief T.
Allan McArtor in the letter that the board considered the FAA's
position on O'Hare's traffic volume ``unacceptable.''
   The letter preceded the safety board's announcement June 8 of an
investigation into a sharp rise in controller error at O'Hare. Air
traffic controllers have made 20 mistakes so far this year,
allowing planes to fly too close to each other, compared with just
12 in all of 1987.
   Investigators, who concluded their on-site work last week, are
looking to see if work overload played any role in the recent
incidents.
   ``I think things are in the embryonic stage as to what the
evaluation is,'' said Michael Benson, a board spokesman in
Washington. ``There is no way to tell where it is going. I haven't
heard of any (single cause) that has jumped out and said, `Fix
me.'''
   The NTSB can only make suggestions; it has no enforcement power.
   In the past, the NTSB has urged FAA officials to re-examine the
limit of 155 flights per hour at O'Hare to see if it is too high,
but the agency has declined to do so, the Tribune reported.
   Burnett questioned the limit last March during a congressional
hearing in Chicago on problems at O'Hare. He said it may be
overloading air traffic controllers.
   ``There is a tendency to take shortcuts, to not follow standard
procedures that slow down operations,'' Burnett said. ``They are
pushing too hard to do what is being asked of them.''
   Meanwhile, The New York Times reported in Sunday editions that
the lagging capacity of the nation's airports could paralyze air
traffic within five years without a national commitment to a
building project on the scale of the program that built the
interstate highway system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
