<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Earthquake 3rdLd-Writethru a0655 06-18 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Earthquake, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0655,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Shakes Gulf of California</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS location of quake in overline, CORRECTS tremor to
quake in graf 5, picks up graf 6 `The quake'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake struck the northern Gulf of
California on Saturday, but Red Cross and local authorities said
they had no reports of damage or casualties.
   David Novelo, a spokesman with the National Seismological
Institute said the quake measured 6.5 on the Richter scale at its
epicenter in Ometepec Bay at the northern tip of the Gulf of
California, 1,300 miles northwest of Mexico City or about 100 miles
south of Calexico, Calif.
   Novelo earlier reported the quake measured 6.0.
   The temblor occurred at 4:52 p.m. local time (6:52 p.m. EDT).
   Don Finley, a spokesman in Washington for the U.S. Geological
Survey, said the agency's earthquake monitors in Golden, Colo.,
measured the quake at a preliminary magnitude of 6.6 on the Richter
scale.
   The quake ``lasted about three or four seconds'' in Ciudad
Obregon in Sonora state, said Froylan Campos, a reporter with the
Tribuna del Yaqui newspaper.
   Alejandra Garcia, a Red Cross official in Ciudad Obregon, said
there were no reports of injuries or damages in the city, located
about 1,170 miles northwest of Mexico City.
   The quake was not felt in the border city of Mexicali, capital
of Baja California state, said Alberto Carrillo, a Red Cross
official in Mexicali.
   ``Absolutely nothing was felt or reported'' in the peninsular
state of Baja California Sur, said Julio Cesar Saucedo, press
officer for the state government in La Paz.
   The Richter scale is an open-ended gauge of the energy released
by an earthquake, as measured by the motion of the ground. Every
increase of one number means the ground motion is 10 times greater.
   An earthquake of magnitude 6 on the Richter scale can cause
severe damage.
   The quake that killed at least 9,500 people in Mexico City on
Sept. 19, 1985 measured 8.1 on the Richter scale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
