<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-IRA     06-18 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-IRA,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two convicted of plotting bombing campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men from Northern Ireland were convicted
Friday of plotting an Irish Republican Army bombing campaign in
England.
   Patrick McLaughlin and Liam McCotter are to be sentenced Monday
and could receive terms of up to life in prison.
   They were arrested by agents of the Anti-Terrorist Squad in
February 1987 after nearly 200 pounds of explosives along with
detonators, timing devices, three rifles and ammunition were found.
   The explosives and weapons were hidden in plastic garbage cans
in the Macclesfield and Delamere forests south of Manchester in
northern England.
   Prosecuting attorneys said police also found maps of Manchester
and London in the Manchester apartment the two men shared.
   The court was told that McLaughlin, 40, and McCotter, 25, both
from Belfast, were kept under surveillance for four days as they
transferred the weapons from a trawler off the Welsh coast into the
forests.
   Full details of the operation were not revealed at the trial.
Prosecutor Roy Amlot told the jury that the Anti-Terrorist Squad
had ``the wider public interest to consider'' and could not release
information that might jeopardize future operations.
   ``Intelligence for the Anti-Terrorist Squad and police in this
country generally is critical. It might prevent another bombing
campaign,'' he said.
   Amlot said the contents of the arms caches was sufficient for a
``sustained and prolonged'' terror campaign with at least 25 bombs.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is battling to unite Northern
Ireland, a British province where Protestants outnumber Catholics
3-2, with the predominantly Catholic Republic of Ireland. The IRA
is outlawed in both Britain and Ireland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
