<DOCNO> AP880618-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 0127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-FireTrial     06-18 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Fire Trial,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Sentenced For Neglect Of Duty In Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese court has sentenced seven officials,
including two local Communist Party leaders, to prison terms for
neglect of duty in a disastrous forest fire last year that claimed
193 lives.
   The seven were given prison terms ranging from two to five years
by a court in northeast China's Heilongjiang province following a
five-day trial. Four others received prison terms of three to seven
years for causing the Heilongjiang fire which raged for more than a
month in May and June last year.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said today that Zhuang Xueyi,
director of a local forestry bureau, received a three-year prison
term for failing to evacuate forest farm workers, resulting in 43
deaths.
   Also getting a three-year term Friday was Li Yongqing, former
deputy secretary of the Mohe County Communist Party Committee, who
ignored orders to clear out the site of a burned area, leading to
further damage when high winds revived the fire.
   Another local party official was imprisoned for three years for
fleeing in a car with his wife and son, leaving behind 1,000 people
at a threatened forest farm.
   The deputy chief of a fire-fighting section received four years
in jail for ordering three fire engines to protect his house when
fire theatened an oil depot and a grain warehouse nearby.
   Two others were found guilty of hiring unqualified workers who
caused fires by operating machinery without supervision.
   The fire ravaged more than 2.5 million acres of Daxinganling
Forest near the Sino-Soviet border. The Forestry Miniser, Yang
Zhong, and his deputy, Dong Zhiyong, were dismissed for mismanaging
the fire-fighting efforts.
</TEXT>
