<DOCNO> AP880618-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 0131EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Superfund     06-18 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Superfund,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says EPA Skimps On Cleanup Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional study agency is criticizing
the Environmental Protection Agency for trying to save money by not
choosing permanent cleanup methods often enough at the worst toxic
waste sites.
   ``Technical evidence confirms that all too frequently, Superfund
is not working environmentally the way the law directs it to,''
said the report by the Office of Technology Assessment.
   The report was prepared to coincide with a hearing Monday by the
investigations subcommittee of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee. It was released in advance and an embargo requested by
OTA was broken Friday.
   The report examined EPA's compliance with 1986 amendments that
require the agency to prefer permanent remedies designed to reduce
the ``toxicity, mobility or volume'' of the waste, and to analyze
the risk of failure if waste is to be put or left in the ground
untreated.
   Treatment methods might be incineration of soil or turning the
contaminated soil into a glassy solid.
   The amendments were adopted because of congressional concern
that EPA, trying to stretch its funds, too often was applying
``Band-Aid'' solutions or was moving waste from a Superfund site to
a hazardous waste landfill that was likely to become such a site.
   ``Impermanent remedies, which provide less protection than
permanent ones and do not assuredly meet cleanup goals, are often
selected purely because they are cheaper in the short run; in the
long run they are very likely to be more expensive,'' the report
said.
   ``Permanence may be claimed even when technical factors suggest
a high probability of failure,'' it said.
   The authors examined 104 cleanup decisions that fell under the
1986 requirements and selected 10 they said were representative.
   Winston Porter, assistant EPA administrator in charge of the
Superfund program which provides money to clean up sites requiring
quick attention, said the study was ``a very superficial look at
the program.''
   ``I wouldn't mind if they didn't try to draw such sweeping
conclusions ...,'' Porter said. ``I disagree with the
extrapolations they make.''
   Porter said treatment technologies were possible in 87 of the
104 cases, and were selected in 67 instances. ``We're not getting
enough credit.''
   The law also requires EPA to chose ``cost-effective'' remedies
and to consider preferences of states and communities involved.
   ``They continually pressure us to be consistent but I keep
telling them the communities aren't consistent, the states aren't
consistent and the problems aren't consistent,'' Porter said.
   States pay 10 percent of federal cleanup costs, ``and states
tell us, `I'm not going to pay 10 percent of $80 million,''' Porter
said. ``Whether people like or don't like a technology (like
incineration) varies from place to place.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880618-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 0132EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MarriedPriests Bjt   06-18 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Married Priests, Bjt,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Married Priests Say They Can Be Faithful To Spouse And Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Priests who fall in love and marry say they
should not have to give up their priestly duties, especially since
there is such a critical shortage of clergy in the Roman Catholic
Church.
   ``They haven't been able to accept us. ... What I'd like to see
them do is to begin to open the doors,'' said Carl Hemmer, a former
Jesuit from Fairfax, Va.
   Frank Bonnike, a founder of the Corps of Reserve Priests United
for Service, said married priests feel ``that women and marriage
and family and children have enhanced our ability to minister.''
   ``We have two calls: the call to priestly work and the call to
marriage. We can be faithful to both,'' he said Friday as the group
opened its first national conference.
   About 10 percent of U.S. parishes have no full-time priest,
according to the group, which said the figure is more than 40
percent worldwide. Fewer young men are entering seminaries, and
celibacy is cited in surveys as an important reason.
   Terrance A. Sweeney, whose 1986 survey of U.S. bishops showed
that nearly a quarter favored optional celibacy for priests, called
the church's policy against marriage for priests ``contrary to God
and human nature.''
   ``It's a scandal that the church proclaims the dignity of the
human person and human rights to the world, but within her own
walls and her canon laws ... forbids this fundamental human
right,'' he said.
   Since the 12th century, the Catholic church has demanded priests
take a vow of celibacy, maintaining that unmarried clergymen are
better able to devote themselves to God and the priesthood.
   Priests who marry are forbidden to say Mass or have a parish but
are allowed to perform some sacraments in an emergency. The church
terms them ``former priests,'' although once a priest is ordained
he is considered a priest for life.
   The priests' group says there are between 15,000 and 17,000
married priests in the United States. The National Conference of
Catholic Bishops said it had no official figures and declined
further comment Friday.
   Women who marry priests have their own difficulties, said Pamela
Sweeney, who has been married to Terrance Sweeney for seven months.
   ``I really went through a very soul-searching period. I didn't
know whether I should feel ashamed and guilty and dirty to fall in
love with this man,'' she said. ``I have been called every name in
the book _ seductress and temptress and the devil. It's very
painful.''
   She feels women are not to blame for taking men away from the
priesthood but rather, ``it's that the church is preventing them
from functioning.''
   ``Priests do fall in love, and no law that imposes celibacy can
say that those emotions are not going to take place,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880618-0109 </DOCNO>
