<2ND_LINE>PM-Sex Surgery,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Awards $4,500 for New Sex-Change Operation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents may be considered objectionable.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>INDEPENDENCE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has awarded a transsexual $4,500
to pay for new surgery to repair problems caused by a sex-change
operation in 1979.
   A Jackson County Circuit Court jury on Friday awarded the money
to Davina Gabriel, 34, who claimed the doctor who performed the
surgery was negligent. Jurors voted 9-3 in favor of the plaintiff,
who had sought $430,000.
   The suit filed against Dr. Robert Coleman, a plastic surgeon who
performed the two-stage operation.
   It claimed the manufactured vagina inserted during the operation
was too small for intercourse. The suit said the surgeon failed to
warn his patient of that possibility, resulting in depression and
four suicide attempts.
   In closing statements Thursday, James H. Ensz, the defense
lawyer, said the suit was filed against Coleman to get money.
   ``A person wanted to punish a doctor and by obvious inference
wanted to make a lot of money,'' Ensz said. ``But money is not
going to make this person feel any better about herself. What Dr.
Coleman has done is performed a good surgery. Unfortunately, the
plaintiff can't accept it, won't accept it.''
   Cathleen Connealy, a lawyer for the plaintiff, called Coleman
arrogant and insensitive.
   ``He decided her complaints were all in her head. He is
responsible for her severe psychological deterioration ... and the
emotional hell she has lived,'' she said.
</TEXT>
