<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 0140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit Bjt   06-18 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit, Bjt,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Overtures To Japan Hint At Potential Summit Victory For Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As leaders of the world's largest industrialized
democracies began assembling today for their annual economic summit
meeting, U.S. overtures to Japan for a free trade agreement hinted
at a potential final triumph for President Reagan.
   Already on the summit agenda was a U.S. joust with the Europeans
over agriculture subsidies. The U.S. delegation, probably joined by
Canada, will seek an end to all agricultural subsidies, but the
idea is meeting stiff resistance from France and West Germany.
   Embarking on negotiations with Japan for a free trade agreement
would overshadow any move on subsidies. More than one-third _ $59.8
billion _ of America's 1987 trade deficit of $170.3 billion
represented the edge Japan has in trade with the United States.
   Critics contend this could be sharply reduced if the two
partners opened their markets to each other without protectionist
devices. Reagan has made the seven economic summits he has attended
since 1981 a test of his free enterprise policy, and he has
invariably triumphed.
   While there is no current discussion over such a treaty, U.S.
Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III said Friday in Washington
that a free trade agreement ``would be something that the United
States would be pleased to consider if it were something that the
government of Japan wanted to consider.''
   As Baker made the comments in a television interview with
foreign journalists, Secretary of State George P. Shultz made
tentative plans to meet here next week with Japanese Foreign
Minister Sosuke Uno.
   The trade imbalance was bound to be on the agenda for Shultz, an
ardent free-trader who has kept a careful eye on the robust yen.
   The West German chancellor, Helmut Kohl, the first to arrive,
pledged in a speech Friday at Toronto University that ``we will use
all means at our disposal to promote stable, non-inflationary world
economic growth. We will resolutely combat protectionism of any
kind.''
   As he received an honorary degree, Kohl said the industrialized
countries would have to find ways to avoid overproducing food.
   The summit host, Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, visited
the convention center where the summit will open on Sunday to tell
reporters he hoped it would be ``a world-class event.''
   He said Reagan, who will be making his final summit appearance,
had been ``a good friend and valued ally'' and that future summits
would be ``much poorer'' without him.
   With countries around the world spending $150 to $200 billion on
farm subsidies, Mulroney said, ``It is very important that all of
us, including Japan, recognize that these subsidies to agriculture
are trade-distorting in nature (and) eventually protectionist.''
   The Canadian added: ``They cost treasuries more money than any
of us can legitimately afford and ultimately they're very harmful
to the farmers.''
   Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita arrived late Friday
after a one-day stopover in Vancouver, British Columbia, while
Prime Ministers Margaret Thatcher of Britain and Ciriaco De Mita of
Italy were scheduled to fly in today.
   Reagan and French President Francois Mitterrand are due on
Sunday, just before the opening bell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880618-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 0146EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Drought-Congress Bjt   06-18 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Congress, Bjt,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators on Fact-Finding Tour of Drought Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six senators are touring the sun-scorched
wheat lands of Montana and the Dakotas this weekend to help them
come up with recommendations for federal assistance to
drought-stricken growers.
   ``I'm hopeful that the trip will give us a better handle on how
severe the devastation is in these specific locations,'' Senate
Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., said Friday.
   He told a House-Senate task force convened to assess the problem
that he wanted to ``see firsthand how the drought has affected
wheat and forage land.''
   Task force members said there was no time to lose in producing a
blueprint for combating drought-related financial and food-supply
problems.
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng, also on hand, has been
saying it is too early to start pushing a drought-aid bill but that
lawmakers should be prepared to act once the full extent of the
damage is clear.
   Lawmakers plan to unveil a few initial recommendations next
Wednesday.
   It remains unclear just how much damage the drought will cause.
USDA authorities still say an inch or so of rain once a week for
the rest of the growing season could bring back Midwest corn and
soybeans.
   Peril to wheat in Montana and the Dakotas is greater, and cattle
growers in several states are searching for feed to replace hay
that has withered under the blazing sun.
   Lawmakers from the afflicted wheat states already are calling
the drought the worst since the dust bowl era and warning that much
of their crop will now be lost even if the skies open up.
   Farmers complain that the drought could crimp their income
potential in two ways.
   Forecasts of a smaller harvest have driven up crop prices, which
in turn has decreased the size of income-support payments some
farmers receive.
   That is because the amount of the farmer's payment is the
difference between the market price of the crop and higher ``target
prices'' that are set by Congress and adjusted annually by the
secretary of agriculture.
   As the market price creeps closer and closer to the target
price, the amount of the payment automatically shrinks. At the same
time, the crop itself is wilting under the blazing sun, making it
impossible for the farmer to take advantage of the higher market
price.
   The scenario grows darker for the farmer who has received a
portion of the income-support payment in advance, used the money to
patch a barn roof or buy new machinery and now may be required to
return part to the government.
   Sen. Richard G. Lugar, R-Ind., told the task force it would
``come ultimately to a problem of income security for farmers and a
question of how deficiency (income support) payments will be made.''
   ``The drought task force will work to give farmers a degree of
income safety even in the midst of a drought that extends for
several weeks,'' he said. Lugar said about two-thirds of Indiana's
corn and soybeans is rated in poor condition.
   House Agriculture Committee Chairman E. ``Kika'' de la Garza,
D-Texas, called for bipartisan action in cooperation with the
administration ``to make sure that the federal government responds
to the catastrophe that many American farmers today face.''
   He said the task force goals should be to assess the drought's
impact on trade and food prices and to formulate an aid package for
farmers.
   ``We have to have a battle plan before too long,'' said Sen.
David Pryor, D-Ark. He said the panel must not neglect the health
effects ``a long-protracted heat wave has on the rural elderly.''
   Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., declared that it was time for the
federal government to join with local governments and the private
sector in providing irrigation assistance to farmers.
   Some use of the federal crop insurance program to aid
drought-stricken farmers was suggested by Sens. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa,
and Thad Cochran, R-Miss.
   The sign-up deadline for the crop insurance program has long
since expired and in many cases the crops already have begun
growing. But the lawmakers said there still might be a way.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
