<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Watermelon     06-18 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Watermelon,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beijing Braces For Summer Watermelon Deluge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Special road passes and extra gas rations are
being issued while mule trains and tractor caravans stand poised to
quench Beijing's voracious summer appetite for watermelons.
   Beijing area farmers this year will produce 660 million pounds
of watermelon for the capital's 10 million people, up 20 percent
from 1987, the official China Daily quoted Beijing Vice Mayor Huang
Chao as saying.
   Huang said the city will bring in another 110 million pounds
from other provinces to ward off any possibility of last-minute
shortages.
   The report said the peak for Beijing's annual summertime craving
for watermelons will come on July 10, when fruit stands, peddler
carts and food stores will be weighed down with about 44 million
pounds of the fruit.
   To cope with transport problems, 23 streets have been designated
as routes for out-of-town trucks carrying watermelons from July 1
to Nov. 15. Tractors and mule-drawn carts, normally banned from
city streets, will be allowed to haul in their crop between 8 p.m.
and 4 a.m. from June 25 to Aug. 5.
   Watermelons, or ``western melons,'' in Chinese, are grown
throughout northern and western China. Tradition has it that the
sweetest hail from the hot, dry climes of western Gansu province
near the Dunhuang caves.
   Chinese have elevated the act of choosing a melon for ripeness
and taste to an art form and often spend several minutes handling,
shaking and listening to and smelling the melons before they make a
purchase.
   The China Daily, in a 1982 ode to what Chinese call the ``king
of melons,'' said it ``is used traditionally as a preventive tonic
against sunstroke and heat exhaustion ... (and) it is good for
chronic diseases like high blood pressure, pyelitis, hepatitis and
cholecystitis.''
   The Chinese take their watermelon so seriously that last year
two men were sentenced to life imprisonment for leading 100 vendors
in the theft of 55,000 pounds of watermelon from a Beijing train
depot.
   The taste for watermelon has created other social problems. Last
summer Beijing sanitation workers had to dispose of about 50,000
tons of rinds. In Shanghai, China's largest city, about 1,000
people were treated in hospitals during one summer month after
tripping on discarded rinds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
