<1ST_LINE>u w AM-KidnapperSentenced     06-18 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kidnapper Sentenced,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baby's Abductor Sentenced To 15 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UPPER MARLBORO, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A District of Columbia woman who was
convicted of kidnapping an ailing 3-week-old baby from a hospital
room last summer was sentenced Friday to 15 years in prison.
   Linda Faye Stancil, 34, was sentenced by Prince George's County
Circuit Judge G.R. Hovey Johnson to 30 years in prison, but 15
years of the sentence were suspended.
   A jury last month convicted her of kidnapping, false
imprisonment and child abduction in the disappearance of Jeremiah
Thate, who was taken from the Prince George's County Hospital
Center in June 1987.
   The baby, the child of Theresa and Robert Thate then of
Hyattsville, Md., was discovered two months later in a Washington
apartment when a District of Columbia fireman noticed a baby he
suspected was Jeremiah when he responded to a fire in the woman's
building.
   Stancil took the baby after suffering a miscarriage and,
according to testimony at her trial, was pregnant at the time of
the abduction but did not know it.
   Ms. Stancil said tearfully prior to her sentencing that ``I
didn't want to hurt (anybody). I did it out of love.''
   Ms. Stancil's attorney, E. Allen Shepherd, said her conviction
will be appealed.
</TEXT>
