<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-ImeldaMarcos     06-18 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Imelda Marcos,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Imelda Marcos Writing Autobiography</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imelda Marcos says she is writing an
autobiography, and promises it won't be boring.
   ``I don't know anyone like me,'' she told reporters at the
Marcos home-in-exile here.
   ``I have lived a full life, richly and totally lived, through
great glory and grandeur and now humility and deprivation,'' said
the wife of deposed Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos.
   The Marcoses were deposed from their homeland in February 1986,
but have been allowed to live in Hawaii by the U.S. government.
   ``Like the life of the Marcoses, the book will not be dull,''
she said Thursday.
   The book is being written with Jack Cox, president of Jack Cox
Productions in Abilene, Texas. Cox, who said he was introduced to
Mrs. Marcos by a friend, expects the book to be in stores by
January.
   Mrs. Marcos and Cox wouldn't disclose what advance payment, if
any, she will receive.
   Mrs. Marcos also said Thursday that her daughter, Imee Manotoc
Marcos, is two months pregnant. Ms. Marcos, who has two children,
is living somewhere in North Africa, said Mrs. Marcos, who declined
to specify the country.
</TEXT>
