<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Norway-AfricanWaste     06-18 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Norway-African Waste,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Norwegian Ship Will Remove Disputed Waste From Guinea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norway has agreed to remove 14,000 tons of
U.S. trash from Guinea which the west African nation charged was
toxic, officials said.
   A Norwegian ship, the 27,000-ton ``Banja,'' will arrive at the
island of Kassa near Conakry on Sunday to begin the 12-day job of
loading the waste, said Tom Erik Klaveness, spokesman of the
Klaveness shipping group on Friday.
   Klaveness said the waste was from slag-ash the incinerators of
Philadelphia. The ash can be used to produce light concrete for
construction material.
   ``The slag-ash was not `dumped' in Guinea. It was a regular
import by a Guinean company named SIAG,'' Klaveness said.
   He said a Norwegian company has applied to import the waste to
Norway. ``We view such an initiative with great interest,''
Klaveness said.
   Guinean authorities arrested Klaveness' representative Sigmund
Stroemme two weeks ago and charged him as an accomplice in the
illegal import of toxic waste.
   Stroemme was assigned to Conakry to run the local firm Ginomar,
which exports bauxite and is owned by both Guinea and the Klaveness
group.
   Stroemme also is Norway's honorary consul general in Conakry,
but he has no diplomatic status or immunity. Norway's ambassador to
the Ivory Coast, Kjell Oestrem, was dispatched to try and get
Stroemme released.
   Bjoern Skogmo, the Foreign Ministry's acting spokesman,
confirmed Klaveness has arranged to take the waste from Guinea.
   ``The ship will arrive Sunday. We now sincerely hope that
Stroemme will be released quickly,'' Skogmo said.
</TEXT>
