<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   06-18 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Promises Action In Fraud Case; Dukakis Pledging Drive Against
Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL C. CRAFT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, heading to Illinois to see what the
drought is doing to farmers and to address state Republicans, is
vowing anyone convicted in the Pentagon fraud case will feel ``the
full force of the law'' if Bush wins the White House. Democratic
presidential nominee-to-be Michael Dukakis, touching prime Southern
bases, promises a no-surrender fight against drugs.
   ``I will not tolerate lawlessness _ in the Pentagon, in the
streets or in the Congress,'' Bush said in Washington Friday about
allegations of corruption in Pentagon procurement programs.
   ``The public should know that a Bush administration will see to
it that any and all charges are aggressively prosecuted and that
the full force of the law is applied to anyone convicted,'' Bush
added.
   The defense probe concerns the alleged sale of confidential
Pentagon information to military contractors through their paid
consultants.
   Bush, the all-but-certain GOP presidential nominee, planned to
stop by a drought-hit farm today and speak at the Republican state
convention in Springfield, Ill. Bush won the Illinois primary March
15.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor who has been on a
campaign march through the South, arranged to attend the funeral of
Hispanic leader Willie Velasquez today in San Antonio, Texas, and
then to address the Democratic state convention in Houston.
   Dukakis, the Texas primary winner March 8, had been scheduled to
be introduced at the convention by Velasquez, who died Wednesday.
Velasquez is credited with registering thousands of Hispanic voters.
   Jesse Jackson planned to speak today to the Illinois Democratic
Convention in Springfield and then go to an extended black family
reunion in Philadelphia.
   Dukakis went to Mississippi on Friday to propose setting up a
National Alliance Against Drugs, to be headed by the president,
aimed at producing ``drug-free schools in every community in
America in the 1990s.''
   ``Nobody is going to tell me we have to run up the white flag of
surrender on this issue,'' he told the Mississippi Municipal
Association convention in Biloxi.
   ``There's a sense that things are out of control'' in the effort
to deal with the nation's drug situation, he said, and ``our
citizens can't walk down the street and buy a bottle of milk
without being in fear of their lives.''
   In other political developments Friday:
   _Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., said he has informed the Dukakis campaign
that he is not interested in becoming the Democratic vice
presidential nominee. However, Nunn stopped short of saying he
would refuse to accept the nomination if offered to him by Dukakis.
   ``I think it's very presumptuous to sort of set up a
hypothetical example of what one would do if one were offered
something that one is not seeking and one is discouraging,'' Nunn
said. ``So I haven't gone to the extent of making a Sherman-like
statement. I feel it's kind of presumptuous and at this stage
unnecessary.''
   _Maureen Reagan, the president's daughter, said in Coeur
d'Alene, Idaho, that Bush should at least consider a woman as a
running mate.
   Despite her statement, she said, she would not press the issue
with Bush. ``I didn't impose my opinion on Ronald Reagan in 1980,
so I don't think I ought to impose my opinion on George Bush in
1988,'' she said.
   _Dukakis was endorsed by Mississippi Gov. Ray Mabus, who said
that ``in a decade that has sanctified selfishness ... Mike Dukakis
has reminded us of our interdependence and our responsibility to
each other.''
   _Religious broadcaster Pat Robertson urged conservative
Minnesota Republicans who had backed his unsuccessful presidential
candidacy to support Bush in November.
   Robertson said: ``It matters whether the man in the White House
is a mediocre liberal who returns us to the policies of Jimmy
Carter, or a distinguished conservative who builds upon the
foundation of a great Republican, Ronald Reagan.''
</TEXT>
