<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Hostages Bjt   06-18 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Hostages, Bjt,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Delegation to Seek Ways of Freeing Lebanese Captives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A delegation of lawmakers will go to Iran this
weekend at that country's invitation to explore ways of freeing
British hostages held in Lebanon.
   However, an official of the Church of England, which organized
the trip, said Friday that the four legislators would not conduct
formal negotiations for the release of the men, apparently held by
pro-Iranian kidnappers.
   During the four-day visit to the Iranian capital of Tehran,
beginning Sunday, the legislators will meet high-ranking Iranian
officials.
   The four lawmakers in the mission are Cyril Townsend and Robert
Hicks of the governing Conservative Party, Thomas Clarke of the
Labor Party and Lord Tordoff of the Social Liberal Democrats.
   Clarke said the invitation had come from Parliament speaker
Hashemi Rafsanjani.
   Diplomatic ties between Britain and Iran were reduced to
caretaker status a year ago but showed signs of improving when the
countries agreed during talks in London last week to compensate
each other for damages to their diplomatic offices.
   The Iranian Embassy building at London's Princes Gate caught
fire when British commandos stormed it in 1980 to end a hostage
siege. British diplomatic buildings and the British Embassy in Iran
were damaged by mobs in 1978, 1979, and 1980.
   
   The British Foreign Office said the lawmakers' trip was
privately organized. ``We have been informed but not consulted,''
said an official there who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``The group is not going to negotiate for the return of
hostages,'' said Eve Keatley, a spokeswoman for Archbishop of
Canterbury Robert Runcie, the spiritual leader of the Church of
England, also known as the Anglican Church.
   ``It is a fact-finding mission to find ways to improve relations
with Iran which could lead to the freeing of Terry Waite and the
other British hostages,'' she said.
   Waite, 49, Runcie's personal envoy, disappeared in Beirut 17
months ago while on his fifth mission to try to win the release of
Westerners abducted in Lebanon.
   Most of the 18 missing foreigners are believed to be held
captive by the Hezbollah, or Party of God, an Iranian-backed
militant Shiite Moslem faction.
   Nine of the missing are Americans, including the longest-held
hostage, Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press. He was kidnapped in Beirut March 16, 1985.
   Other Britons who were kidnapped are John McCarthy, 31, a
television journalist abducted April 17, 1986, as he drove to
Beirut Airport to fly home; and Alec Collett, 64, a New York-based
journalist who disappeared March 25, 1985, while on assignment for
the U.N. Relief and Works Agency.
   An Islamic extremist organization claimed Collett had been
killed, but his body has not been found and there has been no proof
that he is dead.
   Brian Keenan, 36, born in the British province of Northern
Ireland but holding a Republic of Ireland passport, was abducted
April 11, 1986. He was walking at the time to the American
University of Beirut, where he worked as an English teacher.
   The mother and sisters of Keenan appealed Friday to the
kidnappers to declare their demands for his release. The appeal,
published in the An-Nahar newspaper said, ``We are poor people, but
are willing to do everything we can to help Brian.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has stressed her determination
not to pay ransom to the captors of Britons. Waite, who had helped
free three American hostages in Lebanon, left instructions
forbidding any ransom payment if he was kidnapped.
   Mrs. Keatley said the Anglican church has ``repeatedly made it
clear we are not prepared to be party to any deal which would
indicate in any way that hostage-taking pays dividends.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
