<2ND_LINE>PM-Guatemala,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Propose 90-Day Cease-Fire, Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels have issued a call for a
90-day cease-fire and direct talks with the government to end more
than 25 years of civil warfare.
   There was no indication on Friday that the civilian government
of President Vinicio Cerezo will accept the rebels' latest call to
renew peace talks. The first round ever held in 27 years of war
took place last October in Madrid, Spain, without visible results.
   The influential military, which held direct control of the
government until permitting Cerezo's inauguration in January 1986,
opposes more talks.
   A scheduled meeting between the rebels and a national
reconciliation commission was canceled after a failed military coup
in May.
   The text of the letter from the commanders of the rebel
coalition Guatemalan National Revolutionary Union to the head of
the reconciliation commission was published in the daily newspapers
El Grafico and Prensa Libre Friday.
   The letter accuses the government of defying a regional peace
plan signed by Cerezo and the presidents of four other Central
American nations last year. The accord calls for negotiations to
end the region's civil wars, of which Guatemala's is the longest.
   The rebel union's statement says the army has secretly
intensified the war in a bid for all-out victory.
   The rebel commanders propose direct, high-level talks with the
government during a cease-fire that would begin on July 1. The
talks would focus on human rights guarantees and on a schedule for
``dismantling the instruments of control of the population that now
exist.''
   Human rights groups accuse the military of committing massive
violations in a bloody anti-guerrilla campaign that began in the
late 1970s. The violence has diminished, but selective killings and
disappearances are still reported.
   In the letter, the guerrillas also set out their conditions for
a political solution to Guatemala's conflict. They said the
government must recognize the historical causes of the conflict,
demonstrate a desire to end the war and recognize the rebel union
as a party to any negotiated settlement.
</TEXT>
