<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 18-19</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Roller-Coaster Ride For The Credit Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates plunged and soared this past week
in roller-coaster fashion, and running the controls was the nemesis
of all bondholders: inflation.
   For the first half of the week, the mood had been downright
exhilarating. Bond prices registered one of their biggest gains of
the year _ rising around $20 per $1,000 face amount _ while yields
hit two-month lows on reports that substantial progress was being
made in lowering the nation's trade gap.
   But it was easy come, easy go. Nearly all those profits were
lost by the end of the week, and interest rates edged up past the 9
percent level again, amid concerns that overseas central banks were
seeking a tighter clamp on credit to keep their economies from
overheating.
   Runaway economic growth can lead to inflation, which erodes the
value of fixed-income securities like bonds and notes.
   Bond analysts and traders said they couldn't recall a more
volatile period in recent months than this past week.
   ``It seems like a lifetime really when you think about what's
taken place,'' said Marshall B. Front, an economist at Stein Roe &
Farnham in Chicago. ``This has been a roller coaster of a week.''
   Hardest hit by the rise and fall of bond prices and rates were
those who had stayed out of the market, despite a steady price gain
since Memorial Day, but decided it was time to invest after
Tuesday's positive trade data.
   The report by the Commerce Department said the merchandise trade
deficit shrank unexpectedly to $9.89 billion, the lowest point
since December 1984. Most encouraging to bondholders was the fact
the improvement came from a decline in imports rather than a rise
in exports, indicating that the inflation was under control.
   ``A lot of people who had first gotten into the market in any
significant way on Tuesday were just demolished. They had
instantaneous losses,'' Elliott Platt, an economist for Donaldson
Lufkin & Jenrette Securities Corp., said, noting the losses were
felt by institutional and individual investors alike.
   ``It was very disparaging to market psychology.''
   Behind the selloff were reports out of West Germany that the
central Bundesbank would raise a key interest rate amid growing
concern about better-than-expected economic growth in that country
and recent weakness in the mark against the dollar.
   Analysts said bond traders were worried that Japan and Britain
also would raise their rates to keep inflation in check, and that
the Federal Reserve would have to follow suit to remain
competitive. However, in Washington, the Fed indicated it was not
making any significant policy changes right now.
   Adding another negative tone to the credit markets this past
week was a government report showing the nation's factories, mines
and utilities operated at 82.9 percent of capacity in May, higher
than at any time in the past eight years. That indicated that the
manufacturing sector was heating up.
   The Midwest drought also exacerbated inflation fears as
agriculture futures soared in price, although to a lesser degree
than other factors, analysts said. ``When the drought first
happened the market was saying, `Uh, oh. It's inflation,''' Platt
said. ``The market now is beginning to distinguish between
inflation in agricultural prices and basic commodities such as base
metals.''
   Besides, he said, the markets realize there's little that could
be done to prod Mother Nature. ``A change in monetary policy isn't
going to bring rain.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions June 18-19</NOTE>
