<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 18-19</NOTE>
<HEAD>Higher Food Prices Foreseen But Runaway Inflation Unlikely</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be followed later in cycle with an ADD summarizing
weekly price trends.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers will begin feeling the Midwestern drought in the form
of higher food prices before the year is out, but even severe crop
losses wouldn't have a large impact on the overall inflation rate,
economists say.
   Irreversible damage already done to oat, wheat and corn crops
will add a half to a full percentage point to food inflation this
year and help push food prices up 5 percent to 8 percent in 1989,
according to a variety of private and government experts.
   But food purchased in grocery stores comprises less than 10
percent of the variables in the Consumer Price Index, the
government's broadest measure of household inflation. So even a 10
percent increase in food prices, which is considered unlikely,
would raise the CPI by only 1 percentage point.
   Food inflation ``could get up into the double-digit range (next
year) under extreme conditions, but even then, I don't think this
would lead to a round of rapid inflation increases,'' said Terry
Francl, an economist with the American Farm Bureau in Park Ridge,
Ill.
   As for this year, Beryl Sprinkel, chairman of the President's
Council of Economic Advisers, said on Thursday that a rise in food
prices over the next six months would be offset by lower prices for
other CPI components. Sprinkel said he wasn't changing his
prediction for an overall 1988 inflation rate of 4 percent.
   And in the near term, beginning as early as next month,
consumers likely will see a sharp drop in meat prices as livestock
producers sell off portions of their herds because of the high cost
of feed grains and the scarcity of good grazing land.
   The biggest unknown, of course, is how long the drought will
last. The National Weather Service has predicted a continuation of
the unusually warm, dry Midwestern weather pattern through at least
July 15, raising the possibility of a 20-25 percent loss in corn
yields as opposed to the 10 percent loss sustained to date.
   Soybeans plants, which are both hardier and later-planted than
corn, can hold out for a while longer, experts say. Spring wheat
crops have sustained heavy damage but yields of winter wheat, which
accounts for about 75 percent of all U.S. wheat, have been better
than expected in some states where the harvest is under way.
   Futures traders on Chicago, Kansas City and Minneapolis
commodities exchanges have been betting on a long dry spell and
bidding up prices for future delivery of grains and soybeans. On
the Chicago Board of Trade, corn futures have risen about 40
percent since May 1 while soybeans have advanced about 35 percent,
and cash prices have followed suit.
   Ewen Wilson, the Agriculture Department's assistant secretary
for economics, said consumers probably would see the earliest price
increases in vegetable oils, then in cereal products.
   In fact, Kraft Inc. raised prices for margarine, salad dressings
and mayonnaise by 5 percent to 10 percent in January and February,
and Kellogg Co. has raised its cereal prices by 5 percent on two
occasions since the beginning of the year. Company spokesmen said
higher commodity prices were a factor in those decisions.
   But Wilson and others said the price that food processors pay
for raw commodities represents only about 30 percent of the retail
price of the final products. Labor, packaging, marketing,
processing costs and transportation comprise the bulk of food costs.
   ``I feel some of the consumer food companies are using the
drought as a profit-making situation for themselves,'' said Larry
Rus, a spokesman for the St. Louis-based National Corn Growers
Association.
   Livestock consume almost half of the corn and nearly all of the
soybean meal produced in the United States.
   So the most significant increases in food prices will not appear
until next year, when meat supplies tighten as a result of the
drought-related slaughter this year of animals _ especially cattle
_ that would otherwise have been kept for breeding, analysts said.
   ``The net result this year: abundant beef supplies through the
summer and fall, more than anyone expected and, in 1989, a serious
shortage,'' said Chuck Levitt, a cattle market analyst with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Experts say abundant stockpiles will ensure against a physical
shortage of grains and soybeans even if this year's yields are
extremely small.
   And the higher prices could encourage a sharp increase in
plantings next year and may bring into production some of the 60
million acres idled this year under government price-support
programs, said Raymond Daniel, an economist with the Wefa Group
Inc., a consulting firm in Bala Cynwyd, Pa.
   ``We could flood the market with food by the fall of 1989,''
Daniel said. ``American agriculture has the ability to rebound
dramatically. Those are the nice things we should be reminded of.''
</TEXT>
