<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 18-19</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: ... reminded of.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends for the past week:
   Grain and soybean futures advanced sharply on the Chicago Board
of Trade.
   The contract for July delivery of wheat settled Friday at $3.81{
a bushel compared with $3.73} a week earlier; July corn soared to
$3.09{ a bushel from $2.57}; July oats rallied to $2.98 a bushel
from $2.60; and July soybeans rocketed to $9.71{ a bushel from
$8.84.
   Livestock and meat futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle for June delivery fell to 70.22 cents a pound from
72.32 cents; August feeder cattle plunged to 71.80 cents a pound
from 75.25 cents; June hogs slipped to 49.80 cents a pound from
51.15 cents; and frozen pork bellies plummeted to 43.10 cents a
pound from 50.07 cents.
   Precious metals futures advanced on the Commodity Exchange in
New York.
   Gold rose to $458.30 a troy ounce from $453.30; silver bounded
to $7.255 a troy ounce from $7.015.
   Energy futures had a mixed week on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil slipped to $16.45 a barrel
from $16.73; heating oil fell to 43.64 cents a gallon from 44.25;
and unleaded gasoline advanced to 49.97 cents a gallon from 49.22
cents.
</TEXT>
