<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices closed lower as buyers left the
market and a negative atmosphere settled in.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil, finished 21 cents
lower Friday at $16.45 per 42-gallon barrel. On Thursday, the July
contract rose 13 cents amid rumors that Iranian leader Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini had died.
   The near-term contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline slipped
0.22 cent a gallon to close at 49.97 cents, and home heating oil
declined 0.48 cent to finish at 43.64 cents a gallon.
   The market had a bearish tone and seemed to be in search of a
trading range, said Richard Redoglia, a trader for Merrill Lynch
Energy Futures. He predicted that range would fall below $17.20 for
crude, and could even dip below $16 a barrel.
   Technical buying from early in the week had dried up, he said.
   There's ``probably no reason to be an aggressive buyer,''
Redoglia said. ``People will look at rallies as opportunities to
sell in the short term.''
</TEXT>
