<FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-88 0600EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-TexacoMeeting     06-18 0873</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco Meeting,0901</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco Claims Victory in Vote; Icahn Says Too Close To Call</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos TA2,8</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. officials say they're confident
they have won their proxy war against Carl C. Icahn. But the wily
financier, who is also the oil giant's biggest shareholder, says he
thinks it could go either way.
   Top executives of the nation's third-largest oil company and
Icahn, who owns 14.8 percent of Texaco's 243 million outstanding
shares, were speaking after the company's annual meeting here
Friday.
   Icahn's pursuit of five of Texaco's 14 board seats has been
closely watched by shareholders and the investment community,
mainly because he has vowed to use those seats _ if he wins _ to
pressure the company to put his $60-a-share, $12.4 billion buyout
offer before the shareholders.
   The victor will not be known for weeks, however, because it will
take that long to sort through and tabulate the ballots.
   ``Our advisors tell us the likely outcome of the vote is that we
win,'' said James W. Kinnear, Texaco's president. Asked about the
margin of victory, he replied: ``We think it is substantial.''
   Icahn was a little more cautious, saying he thought the outcome
would hang on a block of shares controlled by the New York
investment firm Kohlberg, Kravis & Roberts Co.
   Kohlberg Kravis has not made public how much of its original 12
million-share stake it voted, or which way.
   ``If it went with us, we definitely win,'' Icahn said. ``If they
abstained, I believe we win. But if it went against us, we
definitely lose.''
   Wall Street appeared to be betting on management. It sent
Texaco's stock $1.50 lower to close at $48 a share Friday on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Final ballots were cast after Icahn and top Texaco officials
made their final pitches during the annual meeting, which was held
in a packed hotel ballroom.
   Speaking at his own lectern set off to the side, the takeover
specialist criticized Texaco's management for refusing to let
shareholders vote on his offer for the Texaco shares he does not
already own.
   ``If we're elected, what we will do is keep our offer out
there,'' he said. ``Why should you not be allowed to decide? Simply
because management does not want to take the risk of losing its
position, its prerogatives.''
   At $60 a share, Icahn's bid puts a $14.6 billion value on the
company. Adding the $1.2 billion he paid for his stake to the $12.4
billion he is offering for the shares he does not own, the $13.6
billion total would amount to the largest buyout in corporate
history.
   The crowd, estimated at slightly more than 1,000, generally
favored management. Texaco has many employees in the Tulsa area, a
fact that did not go unnoticed by its mayor, Rodger A. Randle, who
rose to praise the company during a question-and-answer session.
   Many shareholders sported buttons featuring the familiar Texaco
star. Some went one better, dressing in various combinations of red
and white, the corporate colors.
   Another indication of the crowd's attitude came early in the
meeting, after Icahn protested when Texaco Chairman Alfred C.
DeCrane Jr. interrupted him to say he had exceeded his time limit
for speaking.
   ``A manifestation of the inflexibility that has caused Texaco
its problems,'' Icahn sniffed _ drawing mixed boos and cheers.
   Kinnear, speaking for the company's slate of directors, touted
the ``spectacular progress'' it had made over the last 18 months,
during which Texaco emerged in April from a year under Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection.
   The keystone of its reorganization plan was a $3 billion payment
to Pennzoil Co. to settle a lawsuit resulting from Texaco's 1984
acquisition of Getty Oil Co. after Pennzoil had made earlier moves
to acquire Getty.
   The plan includes sales of $5 billion of marginally profitable
assets and a $1.7 billion distribution to shareholders.
   ``Our plan ... is based on the building of value, both today and
for the future,'' Kinnear said, charging that the Icahn group's
true intention ``is that they be designated as the brokers for the
breakup and sale of this company's assets.''
   Several shareholders expressed skepticism about Icahn's
intentions, even though the offer does propose about $10 more per
share than Texaco's stock has been trading for recently.
   ``If you turned (the company) over to Mr. Icahn, it would be
like giving your Stradivarius to a gorilla,'' said Bill Lenz,
referring to the prized antique violins made by the craftsman of
the same name.
   Several Texaco distributors and wholesalers also spoke, calling
for support of management while noting that Icahn's actions had
harmed their businesses.
   ``Some of my dealers are looking for another supplier (and)
heating oil accounts are questioning whether I'll be able to supply
heating oil this winter, said Carlos R. Leffler, a Pennsylvania
distributor.
   But it was not all clear sailing for management.
   Reflecting a palpable current of shareholder unhappiness, Bill
Collallas, a shareholder from Cherry Hill, N.J., criticized the
comany's ``shoddy and incompetent management'' over the past four
years.
   ``You're demeaning my intelligence by refusing my right to vote
on Mr. Icahn's proposal. And I resent it,'' he told Kinnear and
DeCrane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
